<HEADLINE> Vietnam, New Zealand to Boost Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's National Assembly
Chairman Nong Duc Manh and New Zealand Parliament Speaker Jonathan
Hunt Saturday pledged to further enhance bilateral cooperation
between their two countries, Vietnam News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
At talks with Hunt, who is here on a week-long visit to Vietnam
beginning Thursday, Manh said he was satisfied with the
development of the two countries' cooperative ties in recent years,
which can be seen in the exchange of visits between leaders of the
two countries as well as the implementation of cooperative
programs and projects covering economic development, trade and
education.
</P>
<P>
Manh expressed his hope to boost bilateral ties with the
Parliament of New Zealand through the exchange of visits by
experts and the dissemination of information and experience.
</P>
<P>
Manh also proposed to enhance coordination at fora of the
International Parliamentary Union for joint development.
</P>
<P>
Hunt said he agreed that both sides should further boost
bilateral legislative cooperative ties.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese Prime Minister Phan Van Khai and Vice State
President Nguyen Thi Binh also met with Hunt in Hanoi Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Khai expressed the hope for increased cooperation with New
Zealand and asked it to provide further assistance to Vietnam in
teaching officials English and raising milk cows.
</P>
<P>
Both sides wanted to further promote bilateral cooperation in
education and training, trade and the processing industry.
</P>
<P>
Hunt ends his visit to Vietnam on April 19. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
