<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB to Provide Loans to Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
will provide loans worth 1.045 billion U.S. dollars and non-
refundable aid worth 30 million U.S. dollars for a technical
assistance program to Vietnam for the 2001-2003 period, Vietnam
News Agency (VNA) reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The loans will be poured into 15 projects designed to boost
reforms in the agricultural and finance-banking sectors, the
development of small and medium-sized enterprises, the upgrade of
communication and energy infrastructure facilities, and the
advancement of personnel training and the health care sector.
</P>
<P>
VNA quoted sources from the bank as saying that ADB-funded
projects will help specific localities develop local economies
more comprehensively and efficiently.
</P>
<P>
About 50 percent of the loans will be channeled to Vietnam's
central highland and central regions to help these localities
boost agriculture and rural development.
</P>
<P>
The ADB has provided Vietnam with loans totaling 1.8 billion U.
S. dollars since the resumption of bilateral ties between the
country and the bank in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
