<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke041527--Roundup: Reform Dominates Bangladesh Development Forum By Chen Jian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The two-day Bangladesh Development
Forum ended Friday in Paris, with the government of Bangladesh and
its development partners agreeing that the country's key challenge
was to eradicate poverty substantially within one generation.
</P>
<P>
At the forum, which was attended by delegations from 27
countries and international organizations, the development
partners reaffirmed their resolve to assist the people of
Bangladesh in addressing the challenge of poverty reduction and
economic growth based on accelerated policy and institutional
reforms.
</P>
<P>
The level of assistance for the 2000-2001 fiscal year could
range between 1.8 billion and 2.2 billion U.S. dollars. The
development partners emphasized that the actual level of
assistance will depend on progress in policy and institutional
reforms, and faster utilization of the existing aid pipeline.
</P>
<P>
Aid levels could be higher if the pace of reforms accelerated,
they noted.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that poverty is still pervasive in the country,
participants urged the Bangladeshi government to implement
critical policy and institutional reforms with decisiveness and
urgency.
</P>
<P>
They stressed the fundamental importance of improving
governance, especially transparency and accountability, and
reducing corruption, noting that these were directly linked to
increased growth and poverty reduction.
</P>
<P>
The development partners appreciated Dhaka's willingness to
discuss governance issues at the Paris meeting and its
presentation of its initiatives to strengthen institutions,
improve governance and reduce corruption.
</P>
<P>
These initiatives include democratization of local governments,
measures to improve law and order, reforms in banking and loan
recovery, customs and tax administration and public administration,
and measures to curb corruption.
</P>
<P>
The participants also stressed the importance of reforms in the
police force and in election financing, and urged faster
implementation of public administration reforms, the strengthening
of audit institutions, and increasing transparency in procurement.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government emphasized the centrality of poverty
alleviation in its development strategy during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi Finance Minister Shah Kibria told a press
conference Friday that since poverty in Bangladesh is a multi-
dimensional problem and the poor are heterogeneous, strategy for
poverty reduction needed to be flexible, and a multi-pronged
approach needed to be taken to tackle the problem more
aggressively.
</P>
<P>
While recognizing the need for administrative reforms, he said
the timing of the reforms would have to be determined in the light
of socio-political reality.
</P>
<P>
He urged the development partners to continue to help expedite
the pace of development and poverty reduction in Bangladesh,
emphasizing the need for human resources development and speedy
economic growth as they are intrinsically related to the
challenges of poverty reduction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
