<DOCNO> XIE20000416.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Govt Ratifies Economic Reform Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government ratified
on Saturday an economic reform package which will be presented at
the Nepal Development Forum meeting to be held on April 17-19 in
Paris, Finance Minister Mahesh Acharya told the press before
leaving for Paris.
</P>
<P>
The package, which contains restructuring of the country's
economic and fiscal sector, decentralization, improvement in civil
service and the effective use of foreign aid, is aimed at
effecting radical changes in the state machinery and the economic
policy in view of the widespread slackness in the socio-economic
sector of Nepal, said Acharya.
</P>
<P>
Acharya is heading a five-member delegation to Paris for the
three-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
The reform package is to "convince donor countries that we need
assistance to mobilize our internal resources and to improve our
aid utilization mechanism, but not to bridge the gap between
savings and expenditure," said Acharya.
</P>
<P>
He said foreign aid had to be linked with development
strategies and priorities in order to help achieve development
goals.
</P>
<P>
"The present government is highly serious about intensifying
the development process through the judicious and skillful use of
foreign aid," he said.
</P>
<P>
As one of the poorest countries in the world, Nepal receives
about 60 percent of its development project funds from donor
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
