<HEADLINE> Iranian City Councilor Arrested in Connection with Assassination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Iran's conservative judiciary on
Sunday announced that Tehran municipal council member Ahmad
Hakimipour had been arrested in connection with the abortive
assassination against a prominent reformist.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic revolutionary court in Tehran said in a statement
that Hakimipour had been arrested in Zanjan province, central Iran,
on the confessions of other people arrested on the same charge.
</P>
<P>
It said that Hakimipour, known as a reformist, was arrested
after he refused to appear in court to give explanations and was
transferred to Tehran for trial, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Local press said that Hakimipour was nabbed on Friday in his
father's house on charge of having a hand in the assassination
attempt against Saeed Hajjarian, deputy chairman of Tehran
municipal council and an advisor to Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Hajjarian, former deputy intelligence minister, was seriously
wounded in a shooting in front of the council hall in downtown
Tehran on February 12, and recovered his consciousness in recent
weeks following a long coma.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that Hakimipour became a suspect in the
assassination because a letter handed over to Hajjarian, which
prepared the ground for the assassination attempt, was signed by
Hakimipour.
</P>
<P>
Iranian security force have arrested 10 suspects, including the
man who shot Hajjarian and the one who delivered the letter to
Hajjarian.
</P>
<P>
Newspapers closed to the powerful conservatives, who dominate
most of the country's sensitive organs, urged the authorities to
find the relations between Hakimipour and other suspects.
</P>
<P>
Widespread rumors here had claimed that the conservatives were
behind the assassination attempt because he played an important
role in the reformists' landslide victory in parliament elections
in February, a result which humiliated the conservatives.
</P>
<P>
Local observers said that with Hakimipour's arrest, the already
hot factional struggle between the reformists and the conservatives
would reach a new peak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
