<DOCNO> XIE20000416.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian, Canadian PMs Meet on Peace, Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Abdel Rauf
Rawabdeh on Sunday met with his Canadian counterpart Jean Chretien
over bilateral ties and the Middle East affairs.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Rawabdeh expressed his satisfaction about the
close ties between the two countries, and commended Canada upon its
aid to Jordan's development projects, including water project
innovations and mining and vocational training, Jordan's official
news agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
After briefing Chretien on Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein's
efforts to push the peace process forward, Rawabdeh said the two
countries also hold identical views on the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also praised Canada's role in chairing the
Middle East multilateral talks on the refugee issue, and reiterated
Jordan's persistent support for the Palestinians to regain their
land as well as their rights to return home or ask for
compensation.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the kingdom is hosting some 1.2 million or some 40
percent of the Palestinian refugees who fled their homelands during
successive Middle East wars after the creation of Israel in 1948.
</P>
<P>
The refugee issue entailed a heavy financial burden to meet
basic needs of the refugees, Rawabdeh noted.
</P>
<P>
On domestic issues, Rawabdeh briefed Chretien on Jordan's
economic reforms, including its privatization of non-profitable
public enterprises, the efforts to amend laws and legislation to
meet requirements of the WTO and to attract the much-needed foreign
investments.
</P>
<P>
On the situation in Iraq, Rawabdeh said Jordan is concerned with
the situation of the Iraqi people and children as a result of the
crippling international sanctions imposed on Iraq after its troops
invaded Kuwait during the 1990 Gulf Crisis.
</P>
<P>
Rawabdeh also called for increasing the trade relations as part
the efforts to boost economic cooperation between Jordan and
Canada.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Chretien praised Jordanian efforts in the field of
economic legislation reforms which were aimed at attracting foreign
investments.
</P>
<P>
He added that Canada will remain a strong supporter to Jordan in
all political and economic fields, expressing his country's
readiness to invest in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian premier arrived in Amman for a three-day visit on
the fifth leg of his tour to the region, which has taken him to
Israel, the Palestinian territories, Egypt and Lebanon and will
take him to Syria and Saudi Arabia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
