<DOCNO> XIE20000416.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peres Urges Barak to Recognize Emerging Palestinian State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Former Israeli prime minister
Shimon Peres Sunday called upon incumbent Prime Minister Ehud Barak
to support the establishment of a Palestinian state more publicly.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed by Israel's Army Radio, Peres, who currently holds a
regional cooperation portfolio in Barak's cabinet, said any just
solution of the Palestinian issues should include the creation of "
a democratic, demilitarized state."
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that Barak should publicly endorse the idea, not
only suggesting doing so, or refraining from using the taboo word "
state". Peres was referring to Barak's favorite word "entity",
which he kept using regarding a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
The problem of Palestinian independence has been a controversial
and sensitive topic since the peace process between Israel and the
Palestinians was launched.
</P>
<P>
However, Peres expressed his personal view bravely over the
issue.
</P>
<P>
"we said we don't want to rule over another people. If we don't
want to rule over another people, let the other people rule over
itself. It means a Palestinian state," he claimed.
</P>
<P>
Thus, he urged Barak to announce his support immediately as
there is no point in waiting. He went further to warn that
equivocation in this problem will only deteriorate the security
situation in the region, making it another "Bosnia or Kosovo".
</P>
<P>
Peres was Israeli prime minister from 1984 to 1986 and succeeded
the assassinated Yitzhak Rabin as prime minister again in November
1995, only to lose the general election to Benjamin Netanyahu seven
months later.
</P>
<P>
Peres, who won a Nobel Peace Prize for his peace efforts in the
Palestinian-Israeli peace track in cooperation with Rabin and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in 1994, usually adopts a more
dovish policy toward the Palestinians than Barak.
</P>
<P>
It appears that Barak recently also softened his stance on the
issue of Palestinian Statehood.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Channel One television station reported Friday that
Barak told U.S. President Bill Clinton during their summit last
Tuesday that he will recognize a demilitarized Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Such a "Palestinian entity", according to Barak, should be
established on the territories evacuated by Israel Defense Forces,
which will amount to 70 percent to 80 percent of the West Bank and
Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
However, the Palestinian side has been insisting that according
to the Oslo accords, an independent Palestinian state should be
established on all of the West Bank with east Jerusalem as its
capital.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Palestinians have full or partial control of near 40
percent of the territories. Arafat reiterated several times lately
that an independent Palestinian state will be established no later
than September 13, 2000, the day set for the two sides to sign a
final accord for permanent status issues.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli and Palestinian negotiators Saturday just ended the
second round of their final-status negotiations at Bolling Air
Force Base near Washington. The negotiations are intended to
resolve the most thorny issues such as the status of Jerusalem,
border, security, water and the return of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
They are scheduled to reach a framework agreement by mid-May and
a final deal in September. However, the negotiations are proceeding
only at a crawling pace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
