<DOCNO> XIE20000416.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Major Labor Organization Ready for Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 16 (Xinhua) -- A South African major labor
organization announced on Sunday that it was ready for wage
negotiations which it said would be characterized by
deliberations around policy issues particularly labor,
remuneration and government's restructuring plans.
</P>
<P>
The National, Education, Health and Allied Workers' Union
(NEHAWU) spokesman Moloantoa Molaba said in a statement at the
end of a two-day meeting that the organization was ready to start
wage negotiations in all sectors in which it was active.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was aimed at consolidating demands and develop
strategy of the labor organization.
</P>
<P>
Molaba said that in future labor negotiations, to be centered
around policy issues, NEHAWU would strive to close the apartheid
wage gap.
</P>
<P>
Public service sector negotiations would largely revolve
around labor and remuneration policy, Molaba said.
</P>
<P>
In the process, NEHAWU would "reject any attempt to fragment
the public service ... and unilateral restructuring by
government," Molaba added.
</P>
<P>
In the private welfare sector, which NEHAWU claims pays
appallingly, the organization would demand the minimum wage be
lifted from 500 rand (about 76 U.S. dollars) to 1,500 rand (about
230 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"We shall also campaign for a ministerial determination for a
minimum wage in this sector," he said.
</P>
<P>
The tertiary education sector bargaining strategy would be
underpinned by the defence of existing jobs and the transformation
of higher education and pursuit of rationalization of
institutions, he said.
</P>
<P>
The private health sector, in which NEHAWU claimed that union
bashing and huge job cuts were prevalent, would see the
organization campaign for an end to job cuts and raising of the
minimum wage to 1,500 rand.
</P>
<P>
"We shall also want to campaign and call on the government to
regulate the development of private health and its interface with
public health," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
