<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Minister Faces Indictment on Sexual Harassment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Transportation Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai is facing indictment on three counts of sexual
assault and sexual harassment based on complaints filed by three
women, police spokeswoman announced Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The police investigation team for the case ended their probe
Sunday afternoon and turned the findings to the State Attorney's
Office, saying that they collected enough evidence to support their
recommendations to charge Mordechai with indecent sexual acts.
</P>
<P>
The first complaint against Mordechai, a former defense
minister, surfaced on March 7, when a 23-year-old ministry staff
worker in Mordechai's office sobbed out to police that the minister
had sexually assaulted her against her will in his Tel Aviv office
for several times.
</P>
<P>
After the police began to investigate the case, two other women
submitted their own complaints against Mordechai about sexually
harassment acts, which took place over an eight-year period.
</P>
<P>
One of them claimed that in November 1996, when Mordechai was
defense minister, he sexually advanced on her by inviting the
victim to his home to discuss a job application.
</P>
<P>
The other complained that Mordechai sexually harassed her in his
Netanya home in October 1992, when he was head of Israel's Northern
Command.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai reiterated on Sunday afternoon that he is entirely
innocent and he will fight with all his strength to prove his
innocence and clear his fame.
</P>
<P>
If Attorney General Elyakim Rubinstein finally decides to indict
him, Mordechai said, he will request the Knesset (parliament) to
lift his parliamentary immunity, and resign from the cabinet in
order to ensure a swift and impartial trial.
</P>
<P>
Israeli President Ezer Weizman, who himself was recently half-
cleared by police from indictments on his financial irregularities,
said he deeply regrets the outcome of police probe and he hopes the
minister would be proven innocent.
</P>
<P>
But he emphasized that the law should be same for all,
regardless of their political positions.
</P>
<P>
Saliah Tarif, chairman of Knesset House Committee, said that if
the attorney general asked the Knesset to lift Mordechai's
immunity, he will convene the committee as soon as possible to
discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai had taken a leave from his cabinet post immediately
following the misconduct allegations and related police
investigation on March 7. Prime Minister Ehud Barak currently
assumed his responsibility for his ministry temporarily.
</P>
<P>
It is still unknown whether and when he would resign as head of
the six-seat Center Party in Barak's ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
It is also unclear who will take up his post in the security
cabinet, and whether the cabinet will undergo the first major
reshuffle since Barak took office last July.
</P>
<P>
A former major general of Israel Defense Forces, Mordechai
joined the Likud party in the 1996 general elections and became the
defense minister in former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's
government from 1996 to 1999. 
</P>
<P>
However, Mordechai, widely considered a moderate in the right-
wing government, was at odds with Netanyahu over a number of
issues, especially the peace process with the Palestinians. 
</P>
<P>
In the May 1999 elections, Mordechai defected to the Center
Party and ran for premiership himself. He announced to quit the
race at the last minute, which helped Barak defeat Netanyahu in the
first round by a large margin. He and his Center Party later joined
Barak's ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
Now, Mordechai became another senior figure in the political
circle, which is recently busy with a series of police
investigations, to face criminal indictment.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, Mordechai's political opponent, had been recommended
by police on March 28 to be indicted with charges such as bribery,
fraud and breach of public trust.
</P>
<P>
Two of Mordechai's confidants, his bureau chief Michal Kallah
and his driver Meir Ohayun, are also recommended by police to face
indictment on obstruction of justice because their role in the
case. Both of them reportedly had urged the recent "victim" of
Mordechai to drop the accusation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
