<HEADLINE> Lebanese President Visits Kuwait to Rally Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Emile
Lahoud arrived here Sunday on the second leg of his seven-nation
tour, which is designed to garner political and economic support
for his tiny Middle East country.
</P>
<P>
During his two-day visit, Lahoud will meet with Kuwaiti Emir
Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah on means of fostering bilateral
relations, according to the official Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will also discuss a number of issues of mutual
interest and coordinate positions "towards the Israeli
intransigence concerning the Middle East peace process, especially
on the Lebanese-Israeli and Syrian-Israeli tracks," the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Kuwaiti cabinet, in its weekly session Sunday,
welcomed Lahoud's visit and took it as a "chance to exchange views
on many issues of common concern, especially the latest Arab
development."
</P>
<P>
Kuwait, which has made repeated calls for an Israeli withdrawal
from the occupied Arab lands and implementation of international
resolutions, is "keen on expressing solidarity and full support for
Lebanon" in its struggle to recover territory from the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a so-called security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with a claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks. Israeli cabinet in early March
approved to withdraw from south Lebanon by July, with or without an
agreement with Lebanon and its powerbroker Syria.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese president arrived here from Saudi Arabia after
securing support from Riyadh during a two-day visit there. He will
also go to the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain, Qatar, Egypt and
Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
