<HEADLINE> Economic Cooperation Core of Russia-Belarus Union: Putin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The solution of economic problems
should make up the core of the Russian-Belarussian Union, Russian
President-elect Vladimir Putin said in Belarussian capital of
Minsk on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Economics is a priority in implementing the Russia-Belarus
Union State Treaty, Putin told journalists Sunday at the end of an
enlarged Russian-Belarus talks.
</P>
<P>
No cooperation projects in the military or any other spheres
can be built "on the shaky foundation of the economy, which we
understand differently so far," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He urged the two states to adopt a single taxation, customs
service and tariff policy.
</P>
<P>
"The construction of a union state is a stupendous effort,
which should be carried out without fuss and with care and
consistency,"Putin said.
</P>
<P>
Selecting Belarus for his first international trip after being
elected Russia's head of state "shows Russia's readiness to
continue developing relations with Belarus along the course of
integration started by former Russian President Boris Yeltsin and
Belarussian President Alexander Lukashenko," Putin said.
</P>
<P>
The subjects of his "face-to-face" meeting with Lukashenko were
the implementation of the Union State Treaty, bilateral relations,
political, economic and military cooperation, elections to the
Union parliament and other issues "of prime importance for Russia,
" Putin told reporters after his talks with Lukashenko behind
closed doors at the latter's Zaslavl-2 residence.
</P>
<P>
Putin, accompanied by Russian Fuel and Energy Minister and
Trade Minister, arrived in Minsk for a working visit Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Belarussian Prime Minister Vladimir Yermoshin and presidential
staff chief Mikhail Myasnikovich met Putin at the national Minsk-2
airport.
</P>
<P>
Following visit in Minsk, Putin will travel to the United
Kingdom and Ukraine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
