<HEADLINE> Washington Police Arrest Hundreds of Anti-Globalization Protesters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Police estimated some 600 people were arrested for parading
without a permit, and similar charges, and led peacefully to
waiting buses.
</P>
<P>
With helicopters whirling overhead and police sirens blasting,
chanting demonstrators linked arms and blocked intersections near
the World Bank, a target of the protests.
</P>
<P>
Police fired tear gas to disperse a crowd of protesters who
were blocking intersections in their effort to disrupt the spring
meetings of the World Bank and International Monetary Fund (IMF)
on Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
Washington Police Chief Charles Ramsey said at a press
conference the "use of tear gas is something we don't resort to
unless we absolutely have to."
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the gas was fired, some demonstrators threw
bottles at the police, while others remonstrated with them,
shouting "Non-violent protest."
</P>
<P>
Those who provide identification will be fined 50 U.S. dollars,
while those who don't will be fined 300 dollars, Ramsey said.
</P>
<P>
Protesters complained that there was no warning before the
arrests began.
</P>
