<HEADLINE> Putin, Lukashenko Discuss Union Treaty, Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Russian President-elect Vladimir
Putin and his Belarus counterpart Alexander Lukashenko discussed
the Russia-Belarus Union Treaty's fulfillment and pressing issues
on strengthening bilateral cooperation Sunday in Minsk.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have narrowed their differences on a number of
important problems in their relations and may sign appropriate
bilateral accords soon, Putin told a joint news conference after
the tete-a-tete meeting with Lukashenko.
</P>
<P>
The sides have agreed to do business in the military, technical,
and economic spheres, said Putin, cited by the Itar-Tass news
agency.
</P>
<P>
"We agreed to expand cooperation in the military and military-
technical spheres. We reached a phase of drafting particular
documents, some of which can be signed at a sitting of the Union
Council of Ministers on April 25 and the others -- at a future
Russo-Belarussian summit in Moscow within the framework of the
Supreme State Council," he said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also discussed some pressing issues on Russian-
Belarussian Union State, such as a Constitutional Act, the Union
State parliament elections, the coming sitting of the Union
Council of Ministers and synchronized actions by Russia and
Belarus in the economy, foreign policy and defense.
</P>
<P>
Defense and political plans cannot have a shaky economic
foundation, so economy is the key area of the implementation of
the Union Treaty, Putin noted.
</P>
<P>
"It is, primarily, a matter of common tax policy, common
customs space and similar tariff regulations," he stated.
</P>
<P>
However, "what we are doing, we are building a union country,
is a grandiose project. There must be no rush in such affairs," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Putin arrived in Minsk on Sunday for a working visit, later he
will travel to London and Kiev. 
</P>
</TEXT>
