<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Cape Wine 2000, the
inaugural international exhibition of South African wines in the
winelands outside of Cape Town, has met with resounding success
during its two days of tastings and seminars.
</P>
<P>
The South African Press Association on Sunday quoted
international wine buyers as saying that the guests have come
away with a very positive impression of South African wines,
saying they would certainly import more into their respective
countries as a result of their experience.
</P>
<P>
Cape Wine 2000 was hosted by the South African Wines and
Spirits Exporters' Association (SAWSEA) at Nederberg Estate in
Paarl, with financial support from the Department of Trade and
Industry and the Wine Industry Trust.
</P>
<P>
Over 110 South African wine producers exhibited their creations
to about 300 guests, who were able to taste the more than 350
wines to their hearts' content.
</P>
<P>
Leading local winemakers also conducted seminars dedicated to
South African specialty wine varieties Pinotage and Chenin Blanc.
</P>
<P>
Buyers said they would be expanding the number of South African
wines they imported as a result of their experience at Cape Wine
2000 and the various tastings they had conducted in the winelands.
 
