<HEADLINE> WFP Chief Assesses Djibouti Port Capacity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Catherine Bertini, executive
director of the United Nations World Food Program (WFP) has
inspected the facilities at port of Djibouti, which is to play a
crucial role in getting food aid to famine-stricken Ethiopians,
said sources reaching here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Bertini Saturday arrived in Djibouti from Addis Ababa where she
said late Friday that additional food aid would definitely be
needed in Ethiopia, the country worst hit by the drought which has
also ravaged Greater Horn of Africa, including Somalia, Djibouti,
Eritrea and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The WFP estimates that 12.4 million people have been affected
by the drought, 7.8 million of them in Ethiopia, 2.4 million in
Kenya, 1.2 million in Somalia, 367,000 in Eritrea, 200,000 in
Uganda, 100,000 in Djibouti and 33,000 in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The UN agency believes that 940,000 tons of food aid will be
needed to stave off mass starvation in the region this year.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of the aid to Ethiopia will be shipped via the Port of
Djibouti,
</P>
<P>
and to a lesser extent Berbera Port of Somalia, Ethiopia said.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian leaders have definitely rejected to ship humanitarian
aid via Eritrea's ports of Assab and Massawa which were used by
Ethiopia before the Ethio-Eritrean conflict erupted in May of
1998.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia has been using Djibouti for its international
commerce ever since its war against neighboring Eritrea broke
out.
</P>
<P>
 It was reported that Beritni left Djibouti for Eritrea late
Saturday. She will go on to Kenya next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
