<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Expects to Eradicate Guinea Worm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 16 (Xinhua) --The Ethiopian Ministry of
Health has vowed to wipe out guinea worm in the country in the
coming years.
</P>
<P>
The local Walta Information Center Sunday quoted Desta
Alamirew, an expert of malaria and vector-borne diseases, as
saying that the guinea worm eradication program, which was
launched in 1993, had successfully reduced the prevalence of the
disease.
</P>
<P>
The number of guinea worm patients who got the disease by
drinking unsafe water from wells has currently dropped to 249
from more than 1,200 several years ago, he said.
</P>
<P>
Water filtering materials are being distributed twice a year to
the people living in pro-disease areas to protect them from being
caught by the disease, Desta said.
</P>
<P>
According to the expert, the Ethiopian Health Ministry, the
United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF), Global 2000, a
non-governmental organization operating in Ethiopia are involved
in the program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
