<HEADLINE> Zambian Opposition Announces Election Manifesto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's opposition United Party
for National Development (UPND) announced here Sunday its
manifesto for the 2001 elections, promising to move the country
from what it called hopelessness and human suffering to a model of
achievement, unity, sustainable development and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
The manifesto said that the party, which was founded in
December 1998, will ensure that the overall objective of the
Zambian economy shall be to achieve higher economic efficiency and
competitiveness in order to uplift the fallen living standards of
the Zambian people.
</P>
<P>
UPND, one of the biggest political parties in the country, said
that to this end it will pursue a private sector-driven economy
based on production and efficiency.
</P>
<P>
It said it will diversify the economic base through maximum
utilization of local endowments, particularly agriculture,
fisheries, tourism and small- scale mining.
</P>
<P>
It promised to improve agriculture to achieve sustainable food
security and export and turn tourism into a major foreign exchange
earner by improving tourism infrastructure such as roads,
airports, hotels and lodges.
</P>
