<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Condemns Wanton Destruction of Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The random destruction of trees
nationwide due to paraffin shortages and farm invasions will lead
to serious environmental problems, Zimbabwe's Environment 2000
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The environmental watchdog said while it strongly supported
equitable land distribution, the destruction of trees by farm
invaders was harming the ecological balance.
</P>
<P>
In numerous cases, it said many indigenous trees have been cut
down as landless peasants cleared land for cultivation.
</P>
<P>
Due to unbalanced land distribution, Environment 2000 Secretary
General Charlene Hewat said the country was already experiencing
widespread land degradation particularly in over-populated rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
To avoid the mistakes of the past, she said, it was essential
that all concerned parties came together to implement a planned
and sustainable land distribution program where it was a priority
to protect the environment.
</P>
<P>
War veterans of Zimbabwe's 1970s independence struggle together
with landless peasants have in the last few months invaded about
1,000 commercial farms.
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists said they had left a trail of destruction as
they cut down trees to peg their shares of invaded portions of
land.
</P>
<P>
Fuel shortages which have hit the country since last December
have worsened the situation as the majority of people who depend
on paraffin resort to firewood, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported
Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
