<HEADLINE> Former Zambian President Calls for Mozambique Debt Cancellation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Former Zambian president
Kenneth Kaunda on Sunday joined Southern African Development
Community (SADC) parliamentarians at a special church service to
call for the world community to cancel Mozambique's international
debt.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, seen as a senior statesman in Africa, told the
gathering in Cape Town's St George's Cathedral that the debt had
largely stemmed from Mozambique's fight against apartheid and
racism.
</P>
<P>
The need to cancel Mozambique's debt has become more urgent as
the country's problems had been exacerbated by the devastating
floods in February, he was quoted as saying by South African Press
Association as saying.
</P>
<P>
"It is now time for the world to repay its debt to
Mozambique," Kaunda said. 
</P>
