<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Starts Applications for Presidential Candidacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The applications for presidential
candidacy started in Turkey on Sunday as Mehmet Buyukerman, a
lawmaker from Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit's Democratic Left Party
(DSP) presented himself as the first candidate.
</P>
<P>
When asked if he got the approval of his party leader,
Buyukerman said that "we are a democratic party. Ecevit can
understand me, and this is a constitutional right for people to be
a candidate."
</P>
<P>
With the failure of a constitutional amendment promoted by
Ecevit to give President Suleyman Demirel a second term in office,
a new president should be elected by the parliament before May 15.
Demirel's term in office expires on May 16.
</P>
<P>
Deputies who are over 40 years and have completed their higher
education are eligible to be candidates while the nomination of a
candidate for the presidency from outside the parliament shall
require a written proposal signed by at least one-fifth, namely
110, deputies.
</P>
<P>
The application to the parliament's speaker's Office for
candidacy will end at 24:00 local time (2100 GMT) on April 25.
</P>
<P>
The Parliamentary Advisory Board will convene and determine the
date of voting.
</P>
<P>
Any presidential candidate who can garner a two-thirds majority,
namely 367 votes, in the 550-member parliament in either of the
first two votings will win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
If no one can get a two-thirds majority, a third ballot will be
held and a simple majority is required for a candidate to win.
</P>
<P>
Should no candidate receive the required votes, a fourth voting
will be introduced for the top two votes receivers and 276 votes
are needed to be elected as the president.
</P>
<P>
If the four rounds of voting fail to elect a president, the
parliament will be dissolved and a general election be held.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
