<HEADLINE> FAO to Provide Relief to Iran's Flood-Hit Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO) here Sunday signed an agreement offering 350,000
U.S. dollars to assist the flood-stricken people of Iran's northern
Mazandaran province.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by FAO representative to Iran Jamal
Ahmad and the head of the provincial Construction Jihad
Organization Gholamali Ranjbar with the presence of Iranian
Construction Jihad Minister Mohammad Saidi-Kya.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, FAO will provide 350,000 dollars to finance
emergency relief work, including technical assistance program in
the flood-hit regions in the province, the Islamic Republic News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The money will be used to prevent the recurrence of floods in
the Neka region and will include activities such as construction of
water-shed, technical work and tree planting, Saidi-Kya said.
</P>
<P>
Mazandaran province was hit by serious floods caused by
torrential rains last July, in which 35 people were killed and over
200 others injured.
</P>
<P>
Some 6,000 hectares of agricultural land and 1,000 hectares of
forest in the flood-stricken regions have been totally destroyed
while over 3,000 residential and trade units sustained various
levels of damage in the floods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
