<HEADLINE> Interac PIN Pad Out of Canadian Stores after Exploded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Canada Safeway and 50 other major
retailers have pulled thousands of debit-card keypads from their
stores after the Bank of Montreal reported one "melted down" last
week.
</P>
<P>
Canadian media Sunday continued to ask customers not to use the
Interac PIN pads at any of the grocery outlets across the country.
</P>
<P>
Checkout counters at Canada Safeway were reported to slow to a
snail's pace Saturday after its chain of 212 stores recalled more
than 3,000 suspect pads.
</P>
<P>
The palm-sized terminals are being put out of use following a
warning Friday by its owner, the Bank of Montreal, that one of the
PIN pads exploded at a store in Vancouver, British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
"It overheated and fell off its stand and started smoking -- it
basically melted down," Bank of Montreal spokesman Joe Barbera
said.
</P>
<P>
The pads mounted at cash registers were between four-and eight-
years-old and they would be replaced within two weeks, according
to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The bank started telling retailers to remove all similar
keypads Friday afternoon when it got back test results on the
faulty unit that revealed a design flaw in the battery compartment.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Montreal is leasing about 11,000 keypads
manufactured by a defunct company called Atalla, local media
reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
