<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Keeps Boycott of Monitoring Group in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Israel will keep on suspending
its role in the five-nation committee monitoring conflicts in south
Lebanon, Israeli military sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Israel has to weigh its membership in the committee as long as
Lebanese "terrorist organizations" continue violating the
understandings, a statement issued by Israel Defense Forces (IDF)
said.
</P>
<P>
The government has informed the committee that it will not
return until calm is to be maintained in south Lebanon for a period
of at least one or two weeks without infringements of the
understandings, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
The Grapes of Wrath group, comprising representatives from the
United States, France, Syria, Lebanon and Israel, was formed in
April, 1996 under the truce understandings reached between Israel
and Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas, who are fighting to end Israeli
occupation of the so-called security zone in south Lebanon since
1985.
</P>
<P>
Israel accused Hezbollah and other resistant militias of keeping
firing into Israel's populated areas in the north and defying the
understandings, which prohibit attacks on or from civilian areas.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the Lebanese government and the Hezbollah usually
charge Israel with trampling on the understandings by launching air
strikes against Lebanese civilian targets.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government lodged three complaints with the
monitoring group on Friday and Saturday regarding Lebanese
guerrillas' attacks from civilian villages outside the security
zone, which Israel set up in 1985 with a self-claimed aim to
protect its north from cross border attacks.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, the strategy of a buffer zone turned out
to be a failure as the resistant militias caused mounting
casualties of IDF soldiers in the zone.
</P>
<P>
In February, Israeli delegation withdrew from a session of the
Grapes of Wrath committee after an Israeli soldier was killed by
Hezbollah, the seventh since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Since then, heavy exchanges of fire between IDF and Lebanese
gunmen have become a routine affair in the security zone.
</P>
<P>
To end the nightmare once and for all, the Israeli cabinet
approved a proposal made by Barak on March 5 to carry out a
withdrawal from the zone by July, with or without security
arrangements with Syria, the major power broker in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Tourism Minister Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, a former IDF chief
of general staff, said recently that in such a context, the
monitory group is fast losing its effectiveness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000416.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Assured of Saudi Support in Struggle Against Israeli Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Emile
Lahoud ended his two-day visit to Saudi Arabia Sunday, securing the
Saudi support in his country's struggle to halt Israel's continuous
attacks on Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud, who arrived in the Gulf kingdom Saturday on the first
leg of his seven-nation tour of Arab states and Iran, held talks
late Saturday with Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz, and Crown Prince
and Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz.
</P>
<P>
The two sides discussed the latest developments in the Middle
East peace process and Israel's planned withdrawal from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel has announced unilaterally that it will pull back by July
from South Lebanon, which has been occupied by Israel since its
invasion of the tiny Middle East state in June 1982.
</P>
<P>
A Saudi government official said after the talks that Riyadh
will rally support to force Israel to respect peace agreements and
halt its repeated attacks against Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia blamed Israel for the current deadlock in the peace
process and will contact concerned parties to pressure Israel to
abide by the signed peace agreements, halt its aggression against
Lebanon and withdraw from South Lebanon in line wi international
resolutions, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi-Lebanese talks also covered ways of boosting bilateral
political and economic ties, the Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud thanked Fahd for his country's support for Lebanon during
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Apart from political support, Saudi Arabia also has offered
great financial help to Lebanon. The latest Saudi figures show that
Riyadh, represented by the Saudi Development Fund (SDF), is
currently financing development projects worth 1 billion Saudi
Riyals (266 million U.S. dollars) in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The projects include renovation of educational and health care
institutions, implementation of road and water projects, and
construction of sports facilities.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia was also the largest Arab importer from Lebanon in
October 1999, when it imported goods of 6 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the field of tourism, Saudis still occupy the first place in
the list of foreign tourists going to Lebanon. Last year, over 80,
000 Saudi tourists visited Lebanon, representing 12 percent of the
total 673,000 foreign tourists.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud's next stop is Kuwait. He will also visit the United Arab
Emirates (UAE), Qatar, Bahrain, Egypt and Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
