<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Criticized for Meddling in Third World Counties' Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) was severely
criticized by Bangladeshi business leaders at a dialogue here
Sunday for its "wanton interference" in the affairs of the third
world countries.
</P>
<P>
"The World Bank should be abolished because this global
institution is in fact adding miseries in the third world
countries through pressing its prescriptions instead of
contributing to their development in real term," Abdul Awal Mintoo,
president of the Federation of the Bangladesh Chambers of Commerce
and Industry (FBCCI), said at the dialogue organized by the
Economic Reporters' Forum.
</P>
<P>
At the Bangladesh Development Forum held on April 13 and 14 in
Paris, the WB and Bangladesh's development partners made severe
criticisms on the "poor governance and prevailing corruption" in
the country, adding that the actual level of assistance will
depend on progress in policy and institutional reforms.
</P>
<P>
The WB said in a draft report discussed at the forum that
Bangladesh could add 2.1 to 2.9 percent to its annual Gross
Domestic Product growth if it could reduce corruption level to
those in countries with the highest reputation for honest dealing.
</P>
<P>
FBCCI President Mintoo said at the dialogue that the
bureaucrats of the WB had always been in the dark about the actual
situation at the grass-roots levels in countries like Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
With a kind of hypothetical ideas, they designed their programs
and tried to enforce them on the country, Mintoo added.
</P>
<P>
He vehemently opposed the WB's "big-brotherly" attitude toward
third world countries, saying the institution must not be allowed
to poke its nose into a country's internal affairs as it would
amount to interfering in the sovereignty of the country.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the country's present state of economy, Mintoo
said that whoever is in power, the need of the hour is a radical
reform side by side deregulation, allowing the private sector to
grow to help the national economy reap good results.
</P>
<P>
The FBCCI chief also strongly pleaded for reforms of policies
and elimination of bureaucracy, urging all parties to create a
wider atmosphere for desired growth of the national economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
