<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President not to Order War Veterans off Farms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
Sunday said he will not order the war veterans to withdraw from
the commercial farms they have been occupying.
</P>
<P>
"All the British newspapers were expecting me to order the war
veterans to leave the farms. I will not say that and I will not do
that. Why should they leave the land now. They should wait for
the law to be implemented and only then," Mugabe said to a
resounding applause.
</P>
<P>
He was addressing thousands of his supporters, mainly war
veterans from all the provinces, who had thronged Harare
International Airport to welcome him back from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe's statement contradicts the announcement made by
Vice-President Joseph Msika, who was Acting President during the
period when Mugabe attended a Group of 77 economic summit in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Msika ordered war veterans on Thursday to withdraw from the
farms to clear the way for an orderly resettlement, adding that it
was no longer necessary for the former freedom fighters to
continue occupying the farms.
</P>
<P>
However, in his address at the airport in front of the VIP
lounge, Mugabe supported the war veterans who continued to defy
the High Court ruling and vowed to continuously occupy the
white-owned farms.
</P>
<P>
With Mugabe's statement, some of the war veterans, particularly
the ones in Mashonaland West who had started to withdraw, will
re-occupy the farms.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe dismissed the recent High Court ruling ordering the
government and the police to move in and assist in the eviction of
thousands of villagers and former freedom fighters who have
invaded white-owned commercial farms, saying the issue was
political and therefore needed a political solution.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We respect the law of the courts but we as members of
the government regard the political problems as overriding the
little law of trespassing. The land issue is not a problem that
can be corrected by the law but by the government and people of
Zimbabwe."
</P>
<P>
Mugabe promised that the issue would be resolved when the
recent amendment to the constitution became law, which he said
would be sometime this week.
</P>
<P>
"We will sit with the war veterans and cooperating commercial
farmers and work out a strategy," he said.
</P>
<P>
The amendment allows the government to compulsorily acquire
land without compensation and it makes provision for the British
government to pay the compensation.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said although he respected the courts, the land should
be resolved by the politicians, not the courts.
</P>
<P>
He said ordering the police to the farms could lead to more
violent clashes and may be loss of life, something which the
government is trying to avoid.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that he will not order the police to evict the war
veterans.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe and Home Affairs Minister Dumiso Dabengwa contradicted
each other in February on whether the government would interfere
with the invasions by the war veterans.
</P>
<P>
The war veterans have occupied about 1,000 white-owned
commercial farms since February this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000416.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N. Ireland's Protestant Leader Plans Orange Order Split </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- David Trimble, leader of Northern
Ireland's largest Protestant, pro-British party, is planning to
curb the influence of the 8,000-strong Protestant Orange Order
within it, a British newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He intended to propose reforms that could prevent the hard-line
Orange Order and other groups that oppose the landmark Good Friday
peace agreement from sending delegates to the policy-making
council of his Ulster Unionist Party (UUP), the Sunday Telegraph
reported.
</P>
<P>
Trimble, who last month rebuffed a strong leadership challenge
from an anti-peace agreement parliament member, Martin Smyth, said
the move had been planned for some months.
</P>
<P>
Trimble defeated the Orange Order-backed Smyth in a close
competition for the party's leadership last month. Trimble won 57
percent of the vote against 43 percent for Smyth.
</P>
<P>
"This is not something dreamed up in response to last month's ..
. result. These discussions have been ongoing for a number of
months," he said.
</P>
<P>
The move would affect the strong ties that have linked the
Ulster Unionists to the Orange Order since the party's formation
in 1905.
</P>
<P>
But the decision to reform the UUP, which would mirror Labor's
attempts to disentangle itself from the trade union movement, is
likely to anger some anti-peace agreement elements within
Trimble's party.
</P>
<P>
Trimble told the paper that he intended to put the reform
proposals to the UUP's rules revision committee in June, ahead of
the Orange Order's July 12 celebrations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
