<DOCNO> XIE20000416.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> mee0416 hke -- Barak Mulls More Concession in Final-Phase Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak said Sunday that he is considering making more concession in
the final-phase withdrawal of Israeli troops from the West Bank and
Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Briefing his ministers during the weekly cabinet meeting, Barak
said he is mulling the possibility to hand over more West Bank land
to the Palestinians in the final phase pullback, due to be
implemented by June.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the concession, according to Barak's remarks
quoted by Israel Radio, is to show that Israel is not only
interested in talks with the Palestinians, but also in the result
of the talks.
</P>
<P>
After two earlier withdrawals, the territories fully or jointly
controlled by the Palestinians reached nearly 40 percent of the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of the lands to be handed over in the final
redeployment, the last phase under interim accords, had become the
focus of disputes between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Barak's predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu, reportedly only agreed
to concede another 1 percent of the West Bank. Barak himself flied
test balloons in the past few weeks through his aides that the size
will be no more than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, the Palestinians insist that according to their Oslo
accords, they should get at the end of the interim period all the
West Bank and Gaza Strip, excluding Jerusalem, several settlement
areas and military bases, whose status should be settled in the
final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat repeatedly stressed that he
would definitely declare Palestinian statehood by September 13,
with or without an agreement with Israelis on permanent status
issues.
</P>
<P>
On Friday reports said Barak appeared ready to recognize a "
demilitarized Palestinian state." Such a Palestinian entity,
according to Barak, should have 70 percent to 80 percent of the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Barak on Sunday furthered his suggestion by telling his cabinet
that a Palestinian entity must have territorial contiguity. "No
serious person believes that an entity can be created in the form
of a protectorate or autonomy made up of various patches on the map
without connections between them," a statement issued by Barak's
office said.
</P>
<P>
Barak also said he would not annex the Arab villages near
Jerusalem such as Abu Dis and Anata, which is not in the municipal
borders of Jerusalem and heavily populated by Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The villages are currently under the joint control of Israel and
the Palestinian National Authority.
</P>
<P>
Minister in Prime Minister's Office Haim Ramon and Public
Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami, two Barak's confidants in the
peace process, revealed earlier in the day that the final-status
talks will surely result in an independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators on Saturday ended their
second round of negotiations at Bolling Air Force Base near
Washington, which is designed to resolve the thorniest issues such
as the status of Jerusalem, border, security, water and the return
of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
They are scheduled to reach a framework agreement by mid-May and
a final deal in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
