<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Rejects Foreign Interference in Trial on Jews </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Ministry on Sunday
rejected foreign interference in the trial on 13 Iranian Jews
accused of espionage for Tehran's arch foes -- the United States
and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi said the comments made by some
foreign officials on the judicial process concerning the trial
are "questionable" and will not help the defendants, the Islamic
Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
As already announced, the trial is an internal matter of the
Islamic republic and any interference and prejudgment about it is
rejected, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has warned that the conduct and outcome of the trial
could affect the thaw in relations that began only after the
election of the moderate President Mohammad Khatami in 1997, while
France and Germany have called for a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
The 13 Iranian Jews along with eight Muslims were arrested in
March and April last year on charges of spying for the U.S. and
Israel, who have denied any connection with them.
</P>
<P>
The first session of the trial was held on Thursday at a
revolutionary court in Shiraz, capital of the southern Fars
province, the center of Iran's 35,000-strong Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
The closed-door trial was adjourned and postponed to May 1 upon
the request of a defense lawyer as the timing of the trial
coincided with Passover, a Jewish feast.
</P>
<P>
Asefi said the Iranian Judiciary will handle the case
independently and administer justice concerning the charges brought
up against the accused.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Ali Amiri, head of justice department of the southern
Fars province, on Thursday also promised a "fair, lawful and
impartial" trial for the Jews, and said there is no difference
between Muslim and Jews accused of espionage.
</P>
<P>
He said that four of the accused confessed to their crime in the
first court session and asked for leniency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
