<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IRA Offered New "War is Over" Deal: Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- London would lift the suspension
of Northern Ireland's home-rule government should the Irish
Republican Army (IRA) announce the "war is over" with Britain, the
Observer newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was raised by Britain's Northern Ireland Secretary
Peter Mandelson as part of a new initiative drawn up between
London and Dublin in order to revive the stalled peace process in
the province, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland's departure from 30 years of sectarian
violence halted in February when Mandelson suspended a fledgling
home-rule government after IRA guerrillas showed no sign of
disarming.
</P>
<P>
If the IRA said the war with Britain was over and the Ulster
Unionists agreed with details of the new package designed by
London and Dublin to end the current stand-off, Britain would
allow Northern Ireland's power-sharing executive to resume working,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
But the IRA, the military arm of the Sinn Fein party, should
give a clear commitment to disarmament albeit over a longer period
than was originally intended in the groundbreaking Good Friday
peace agreement, it added.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Northern Ireland Office said that the core
of the new initiative would be to get "clarity" on the disarmament
issue.
</P>
<P>
David Trimble, leader of the biggest pro-British Protestant
party, the Ulster Unionists, has said he would share government
with Sinn Fein again as long as the guerrillas made a strong
commitment to disarming.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams warned that he could
not say with certainty that the "war" was over in Northern Ireland.
Sinn Fein insists that Mandelson breached the peace pact by
suspending the province's home-rule government.
</P>
<P>
Guerrilla groups in the British province were supposed to
surrender their arms before May 22. Both the British and Irish
governments conceded that the deadline would have to be missed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
