<HEADLINE> Bubka to Retire After Sydney Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 16 (Xinhua) -- World record holder Sergei Bubka
said he would retire after the Sydney Olympic Games starting on
September 15, local newspaper reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
But the 37-year-old Ukrainian vowed to win the Olympic pole
vault gold before he ends his honorable career, according to the
Kommersant.
</P>
<P>
"I'll compete in some warm-ups before I set off for the Olympic
gold in Sydney," the 1988 Seoul Olympics goldlist was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The five-time world champion missed the track for one and a
half years for an injured heel and recovered for training in March
in France.
</P>
<P>
Bubka, who set an Olympic record of 6.03 meters in Seoul, South
Korea, failed to claim the same mark in the 1992 Barcelona
Olympics and missed the 1996 Atlanta Games because of injuries.
</P>
<P>
Starting his brilliant career in 1983 when he was 19, Bubka
broke the world records for 35 times and holds the world indoor
mark of 6.15 meters, set on Feburary 21, 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
