<DOCNO> XIE20000416.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Urges Iraq to Clarify Fate of Remaining POWs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- A senior Iranian official on Sunday
Urged Iraq to clarify the fate of remaining 3,000 Iranian prisoners
of war (POWs) left over from the 1980-88 war between the two
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Brigadier General Abdollah
Najafi, head of the Iranian special commission in charge of POWs,
said that Iran has documents and evidences to prove the existence
of about the 3,000 Iranian POWs in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"Iran wants the fate of the Iranian POWs to be clarified, no
matter they are alive or have been martyred," he said, calling on
the Iraqi government to allow representatives of the International
Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) to visit POW camps and prisons in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Accusing Baghdad of suspending bilateral talks on the POW issue,
Najafi said that Tehran is serious and sincere in solving the POW
problem with Iraq as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran released 1,999 Iraqi POWs last week under an
agreement with the ICRC, which promised to follow up the case of
Iranian POWs and to inform Tehran of the result in a month.
</P>
<P>
Iran had announced to release 2,000 Iraqi POWs in a bid to speed
up the settlement of the POW issue between the two countries, the
officer said, but one of them refused to return home and sought
asylum in Iran.
</P>
<P>
He said that Tehran has so far released 57,712 Iraqi POWs on 105
occasions while Baghdad freed 39,417 Iranians on 70 occasions.
</P>
<P>
Iraq handed over three lists to Iran in 1998 claiming the
existence of 20,743 Iraqi POWs in Iran, but over 10,000 had been
released in recent years while 9,000 others refused to return home,
Najafi said.
</P>
<P>
All the Iraqi POWs registered by the ICRC have been released, he
said, refusing to give the exact number of Iraqi POWs stilled held
in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Najafi also rejected the recent accusation by Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein that Iran had tortured and murdered some Iraqi POWs
by using methods worse than the Nazis during the World War II.
</P>
<P>
Iraq claimed that it has repatriated all Iranian POWs except
64 "criminals" who were arrested after the Gulf war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
