<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Budget Crisis Affects Missions Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's 2000 budget crisis
resulting in pervasive cash crunch has taken toll on its missions
abroad as most of them can not meet their financial commitments.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper, quoted diplomatic
sources as disclosing on Sunday that the situation in some
missions has been so bad that even salaries cannot be paid.
</P>
<P>
To underscore the seriousness of the financial crunch, two of
Nigeria's envoys recently had to abandon their duty posts and come
to Abuja to complain and beg for money, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
This year's federal budget was long delayed in passage by the
country's top legislature and was yet signed by the president due
to differences between the two sides on certain items of
expenditure.
</P>
<P>
The diplomatic missions are worried about the implications of
these handicaps on Nigeria's image, which has just suffered some
bashing over Nigerian leader's trip to Cuba on a commercial
flight, due to a veto by the National Assembly to the president's
request for a new jet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
