<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- The "overall expansions" carried out by Dubai Civil
Aviation Authority at Dubai International Airport, the Middle East
second biggest port after Saudi's Jeddah International Airport,
over the past 30 months at over 700 million U.S dollars, entered
service on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Arabic daily Al-Haiyat quoted the authority officials as
saying that they would kick off another expansion project at 650
million U.S dollars in the coming two years.
</P>
<P>
The renovations will raise the airport's passenger capacity from
less than 10 million to 15 millions per year.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Tunisian Industry Minister, al-Munsif Bin Abdullah said
oil exploration schemes started recovering after the relative
slowness in l999 which resulted the sluggish prices in l998.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by Egyptian daily al-Alam al-Youm on Sunday as
saying that there would be about 45 exploration concessions in the
coming months while at least 10 wells would be drilled with an
investment of 110 million dinars against 5 wells at 76 million
dinars last year.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Tunisia's oil output this year would hit 3.8
million tons where as the gas would rise 13 percent to 2 million
tons.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT City -- Kuwait city-based Arab Institution for Investment
Insurance's board decided increasing the foundation's resources by
155 million U.S dollars and restructuring the body through
introducing a new board to replace the Supervisory Commission in a
bid to cope with the future developments and enhance
competitiveness in view of the regional and international changes.
</P>
<P>
In a release, the institution said it received 145 applications
of insurance from investors and exporters from 11 Arab countries at
total value of 309 million dollars in l999. Eighty applications at
combined value of 157 million dollars have been already treated
after signing contracts with the relevant investors and exporters
from 9 Arab countries, it added.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordan Phosphate Mining Company, the largest
phosphate producer of the kingdom, recorded losses of 20 million
Jordanian dinars (28 million U.S. dollars) in the year 1999 as
against 8.6 million dinars (12.04 million dollars)in profits in
1998.
</P>
<P>
Sales by the company rose to 236.5 million dinars (331.10
million dollars) in 1999 from 255 million dinars (357 million
dollars) in the previous year, according to the company's yearly
report which was available on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed losses in 1999 to administrative and
technical hurdles as well as fierce competition from manufacturers
in Morocco, Tunisia and the United States, which are cutting into
Jordan`s traditional markets in South Korea, Bangladesh and
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Currently the company is counting for new markets in South
Africa, Lithuania, Ukraine and Russia while trying to keep its edge
in India, Indonesia and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Yemeni government said it repaid installments and
interests amounting to 1.79 billion U.S dollars, until the end of
1998, from the total of foreign loans.A report prepared by the
Central Agency for Monitoring and Accounting stated that the
annulled installments and interests, after signing agreements with
creditors, reached 5.6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Arab daily "Alhayat" said today the report indicated that
the long-delayed accumulated arrears, until the end of 1998, were
642.7 million dollars distributed to the Arab and foreign
countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- For the first time in the history of exporting the
Egyptian potatoes to the countries of the European Union, Egypt
successfully managed to complete the current exporting season
without a single one being infected by the disease of brown rot.
</P>
<P>
The Arab economic daily "Alalam el-Yom" on Saturday quoted the
minister of economy and foreign trade, Yousef Boutrus Ghali as
saying that Egypt exported 107,000 ton of potatoes to the European
markets, noting that ending the exporting season without any
problems will help restore the good reputation of the Egyptian
potatoes in the world markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
