<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Opposition Accused of Betraying Political Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's ruling Chama Cha
 Mapinduzi (CCM) party has accused the opposition Civic United
Front (CUF) of betraying the Commonwealth-brokered political
accord.
</P>
<P>
The document is aimed at ending the political stalemate in the
semi- autonomous Zanzibar region, the official Sunday News
reported.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued on Friday night, the CCM's Deputy
Secretary General in Zanzibar Hassan Mussa Takrima said the CUF's
opposition to a bill on the proposed Isles constitutional
amendment is a violation of the accord itself.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth-brokered agreement, which were signed by the
two parties in June 1999, calls for the reforms of the Zanzibar
Electoral Commission (ZEC) as an enhancement of its technical
competence to ensure future elections free of controversy.
</P>
<P>
The bill also sought immunity of the president from
prosecutions while in office and after his office terms.
</P>
<P>
The CUF had from the outset no intention to respect the accord
aimed at restoring normal political life in the Isles, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
Takrima said the CUF's move on signing of the agreed memorandum
with the CCM is a ploy to hoodwink the people and the world into
believing that they wanted to bury the hatchet and open a new
chapter of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that the proposed constitutional bill was intended
to consolidate democracy and restore political order for the sake
of people's development in the island state off mainland Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The rejection of the bill means the current constitution which
is the center of criticism would remain in force, said Takrima.
</P>
<P>
In a roll call held in the Zanzibar House of Representatives on
Friday, all the 47 CCM legislators supported the bill while all
the 24 CUF legislators rejected it, making it impossible to get
the support of at least 50 House members.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar joined with mainland Tanganyika to form the United
Republic of Tanzania in 1964. But it has its own government and
parliament. Zanzibar' s CCM, under President Salmin Amour,
claimed a narrow victory over the CUF in the 1995 elections, but
the CUF questioned the result. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000416.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Continue Support for Indonesia's Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro
Mori assured visiting Indonesian President Abdurrahman Wahid on
Sunday that Japan has not altered its policy of supporting
Indonesia's reform efforts despite the recent change in Japan's
premiership.
</P>
<P>
Mori told Wahid that Japan will continue to support Indonesia's
economic reconstruction and its efforts to resolve problems over
separatist activities in Aceh and religious strife in the Maluku
Islands, Kyodo news agency quoted a Japanese government official
as saying.
</P>
<P>
In the meeting, Mori said Japan will continue to support
Indonesia's reform efforts by, for example, holding the next
meeting of major aid donors in Japan in the fall.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting in February, the Consultative Group on Indonesia
pledged up to 4.7 billion dollars in new aid to help fund
Indonesia's projected budget deficit. Of the pledges, Japan
committed the most at 1.56 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Mori also urged Indonesia to implement a reform program under
the International Monetary Fund. Wahid promised to do so, saying
it is a step that is necessary for his country to gain the
confidence of the international community, according to Kyodo.
</P>
<P>
Mori reiterated Japan's position of seeking "the integrity of
Indonesia" in respect to separatist activities in Aceh and the
sectarian strife in the Maluku Islands. He also urged Wahid to
exert strong leadership in resolving problems over East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Wahid said he plans to meet East Timorese independence leader
Xanana Gusmao for talks on his way to or from his planned visit to
Australia, the Japanese official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, the two leaders announced members of a new
panel of Japanese and Indonesian experts to advise the two leaders
on a wide range of issues, including foreign policy and
international finance. The Japan-Indonesia Advisory Network,
consisting of 10 experts, plans to meet twice a year.
</P>
<P>
Wahid and former Japanese prime minister Keizo Obuchi agreed to
launch the panel when they met last November.
</P>
<P>
Wahid made a stopover in Japan on his way back from a 10-day
trip to South Africa, Mexico and Cuba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
