<HEADLINE> Top Legal News Items This Week in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's Supreme People's Court (SPC) started to launch an
intensive investigation on April 11 of newly-emerging legal issues
revolving around China's expected entry into the World Trade
Organization and e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
The SPC proposed 22 topics for a year-long study to be headed
by its president Xiao Yang and vice-presidents.
</P>
<P>
Dogs to Patrol Chinese Borders in Fight Against Drug-
Related Crimes
</P>
<P>
More than 200 police dog handlers from over 10 provinces and
regions of China gathered in Harbin on April 10 to begin a six-
month program on training for border patrol.
</P>
<P>
The officers are expected to bring a large number of police
dogs to be used for patrolling Chinese borders in the fight
against drug and weapons trafficking and other crimes.
</P>
<P>
Formerly only a conduit for international drug-trafficking,
China has fallen victim to the narcotics trade, with more drugs
entering the country each year.
</P>
<P>
In the national fight against drug-related crimes, a Zhangzhou
court in East China's Fujian Province sentenced two drug dealers,
one from Taiwan, the other from mainland, to death in the trial of
first instance.
</P>
<P>
Xiamen police in Fujian also announced that they uncovered a
major armed drug ring headed by a Taiwanese in a raid to an
underground factory manufacturing the drug known as "ice." Police
seized 257.34 kilos of ice, five pistols and 319 rounds of bullets
in the actions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000416.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Legal News Items This Week in China (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Of the 473 million yuan (57 million US dollars) embezzled and
misappropriated by officials in the massive relocation project
linked to the Three Gorges Dam construction in 1998, 338 million
yuan (41 million US dollars) has been recovered, a special
auditing contingent said on April 14.
</P>
<P>
From 1993 through 1999, the central government earmarked a
total of 17.68 billion yuan (2.1 billion US dollars) for the
resettlement of 220,000 residents who live along the middle
reaches of the Yangtze River, where the new dam will be built, an
auditor said.
</P>
<P>
Law Maker Punished for Breaking Law
</P>
<P>
Jing Xianzhuo, chairman of the Standing Committee of the People
's Congress of Xinyang, a city in central Henan Province, was
removed from his post for violating Party discipline and law.
</P>
<P>
Jing has also been expelled from the Party with the approval of
the Henan Provincial Committee of the Chinese Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
 Fire Facilities Checked at Recreation Centers in Beijing
</P>
<P>
Alarmed by frequent fires across the country that have dozens
of human lives, Beijing police examined fire fighting facilities
in nearly 2,000 recreation centers over the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that 5,395 cases of fire accidents
occurred in Beijing in 1999, killing 53 and injuring 92 in
addition to some 31.65 million yuan (about 3.8 million U.S.
dollars) worth properties.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-four people were killed in a fire that broke out on
March 29 in a video parlor in Jiaozuo City of central China's
Henan Province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
