<DOCNO> XIE20000416.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Urges Iraq to Clarify Fate of Remaining POWs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- A senior Iranian official on Sunday
Urged Iraq to clarify the fate of remaining 3,000 Iranian prisoners
of war (POWs) left over from the 1980-88 war between the two
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Brigadier General Abdollah
Najafi, head of the Iranian special commission in charge of POWs,
said that Iran has documents and evidences to prove the existence
of about the 3,000 Iranian POWs in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"Iran wants the fate of the Iranian POWs to be clarified, no
matter they are alive or have been martyred," he said, calling on
the Iraqi government to allow representatives of the International
Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) to visit POW camps and prisons in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Accusing Baghdad of suspending bilateral talks on the POW issue,
Najafi said that Tehran is serious and sincere in solving the POW
problem with Iraq as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran released 1,999 Iraqi POWs last week under an
agreement with Iraq, which promised to follow up the case of
Iranian POWs and to inform Tehran of the result in a month.
</P>
<P>
Iran had announced to release 2,000 Iraqi POWs in a bid to speed
up the settlement of the POW issue between the two countries, the
officer said, but one of them refused to return home and sought
asylum in Iran.
</P>
<P>
He said that Tehran has so far released 57,712 Iraqi POWs on 105
occasions while Baghdad freed 39,417 Iranians on 70 occasions.
</P>
<P>
Iraq handed over three lists to Iran in 1998 claiming the
existence of 20,743 Iraqi POWs in Iran, but over 10,000 had been
released in recent years while 9,000 others refused to return home,
Najafi said.
</P>
<P>
All the Iraqi POWs registered by the ICRC have been released, he
said, refusing to give the exact number of Iraqi POWs stilled held
in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Najafi also rejected the recent accusation by Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein that Iran had tortured and murdered some Iraqi POWs
by using methods worse than the Nazis during the World War II.
</P>
<P>
Iraq claimed that it has repatriated all Iranian POWs except
64 "criminals" who were arrested after the Gulf war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000416.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Invites U.S. Team to Define Border with Lebanon: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Israel will invited an expert
team of the United States Defense Department to help it map out the
exact borderline with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The team is due to arrive in the region at the invitation of
Israeli government in the coming days to begin work immediately,
the Jerusalem Post daily quoted Israeli Defense Ministry sources as
saying on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The idea was reportedly the result of consultations in
Washington last week between U.S. defense officials and an Israeli
delegation, headed by Defense Ministry Deputy Director-General
Moshe Kochanovsky and officials from the Israel Defense Forces
(IDF) cartography department.
</P>
<P>
It is a further preventive move for carrying out Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak's strategic concept of withdrawing Israeli
soldiers from the so-called security zone in south Lebanon by July,
even without a peace deal with Syria, the major power broker in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The buffer zone was set up by Israel in 1985 with a self-claimed
aim to protect its north from cross border guerrilla attack. But
the mounting casualties in the area spurred a growing public
pressure for a pullout.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Israeli cabinet decided to back Barak's pledge to
redeploy troops to the international border with Lebanon by July,
with or without security arrangements with Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the question of where the borderline exactly lies
between the two countries had surfaced on the table of Barak and
some IDF senior officials.
</P>
<P>
According to a unilateral withdrawal plan drafted by IDF, code-
named "Morning Twilight", Israeli troops will withdraw to the 1978
borderline, leaving some large outposts in Lebanese territory.
</P>
<P>
The plan has invited fierce criticism both at home and abroad.
Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas and other resistance groups
threatened to keep fight for ending Israeli occupation, even only
on one inch of Lebanese soil.
</P>
<P>
In response, Barak insisted that IDF should revised the plan to
leave no pretext for attacks against Israel's northern settlements
and win more international sympathy and legitimacy for the
pullback.
</P>
<P>
However, the thorny problem is still not totally resolved, as
there are serious differences over the exact borderline.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese officials claimed that the IDF should be deployed to
the 1923 international border between them, while Israel sticks to
its claim to withdraw to the boundary where IDF soldiers stationed
on the eve of moving into southern Lebanon on June 14, 1978.
</P>
<P>
It is still not clear whether Lebanon will compromise to agree
to a boundary demarcated by U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
To play safe, Israel has been trying to garner support from the
United Nations to endorse its unilateral redeployment in the past
few weeks.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister David Levy will travel to New York in May to
present to U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan an official letter
outlining Israel's planed withdrawal on the basis of U.N. Security
Council Resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, which was passed in 1978, calls for an immediate
and unconditional Israeli pullout from all Lebanese territory and a
return of full sovereignty to Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000416.0111 </DOCNO>
