<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Congratulates Putin on Ratification of START II </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Saturday congratulated Russian President-elect Vladimir Putin in a
telephone call on the ratification of the Second-phase Strategic
Arms Reduction Treaty (START II) by Russian parliament.
</P>
<P>
The two also agreed to hold their first summit before the G8
meeting set for July in Japan's Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
During the 10-minute talks, Clinton congratulated Putin on the
State Duma's (lower house of Russian parliament) ratification of
the long-delayed START II on Friday, describing it as "a historic
event" and "extremely important" for Russian-American relations
and for the entire world community, said Putin's press service
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The two also agreed to step up efforts to ensure strategic
security and to begin the third-phase START talks, and discuss
ways for strengthening the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile (ABM)
treaty regime.
</P>
<P>
Putin has received several congratulation messages on the
ratification from foreign leaders, the U.N. Secretary-General and
heads of other international organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
