<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines on Track for Balanced Budget: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Sunday that it remains on track to achieving a balanced budget
before President Joseph Estrada ends his six-year term in 2004.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, Secretary Benjamin Diokno of the
Department of Budget and Management said that the government is
working to achieve this goal by 2003.
</P>
<P>
"Our plan is to have a balanced budget by 2003, and a surplus
before the president's term ends in 2004," Diokno said.
</P>
<P>
He added the surplus by 2004 would not be like the supposed
excess fund left behind by the past administration, which got its
"surplus" by not paying contractors.
</P>
<P>
Diokno said that the government is able to push its social
programs to help the poor uplift their standard of living by
depending on revenue collection.
</P>
<P>
The country's budget deficit for 2000 is 62.5 billion pesos (1.
5 billion U.S. dollars), or 1.8 percent of its gross national
product (GNP), he said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the country's deficit was 112 billion pesos (2.8
billion dollars), or 3.6 percent of its GNP.
</P>
<P>
For the first quarter of 2000, Diokno said, the government
appears to be on its way to achieving these goals with the over-
performance of its revenue-generating agencies.
</P>
<P>
The Bureau of Internal Revenue collected 83.2 billion pesos (2
billion dollars), while the Bureau of Customs got 21.7 billion
pesos (542 million dollars), registering respective surpluses of 5.
2 billion pesos (130 million dollars) and 1.9 billion pesos (47
million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
