<HEADLINE> Zambia Urged to Improve Educational System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has been
urged to improve educational system by increasing the proportion
of resources allocated to the sector, Sunday Times of Zambia
reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, two visiting British members of
parliament (MPs) have described the Zambian educational system as
a disaster.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Glenys Kinnock, one of the MPs, as saying at a press
briefing in Lusaka on Saturday it was sad to learn that about
665,000 school-age children in Zambia have never seen the inside
of a classroom.
</P>
<P>
Kinnock urged the Zambian government to prioritize basic
education by investing more money in it.
</P>
<P>
She noted that on the average Africa only spent 3.5 percent of
its Gross Domestic Production (GDP) on education while Zambia only
spent 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
It was imperative for the Zambian government to prioritize
education, especially at the basic education level to ensure as
many children as possible were equipped with basic literacy and
numeracy skills, she said.
</P>
<P>
And Oona King, the other British MP, said education was
interlinked to economic growth and stability and in the absence of
these, good governance, transparency and accountability would be
difficult to achieve.
</P>
<P>
King also expressed concern at the alarming toll which the
HIV/AIDS pandemic had on the country's education system and that
if not adequately addressed, the system risked collapsing.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Sub-Saharan Africa is the only part of
the developing world in which the number of children out of school
is increasing.
</P>
<P>
If the current trend continues, there will be 57 million
primary school-age children out of school in 2015, it quoted King
as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
