<HEADLINE> Jordanian Police Seize 109 Kilograms of Heroin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian police have seized 109
kilograms of heroin with a street value of 7.5 million Jordanian
dinars (10.5 million U.S. dollars) at a border point with Syria,
the semiofficial Jordan Times reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The drugs were hidden in a secret compartment of a truck
travelling from Syria toward a third and unnamed neighboring
country via Jordan, Director of the Public Security Department
Dhaher Fawwaz was quoted as saying by the paper.
</P>
<P>
However, police refused to disclose the date of the seizure and
the number of suspects arrested during the operation, believed to
be the largest haul in recent years in the kingdom's anti-drug
campaign.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom said the drug problem is one of the major threats to
its national security, and anti-narcotics campaigns remained as one
of the top priorities of police, customs and intelligence agencies
across the country. 
