<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak indicated to U.S. President
Bill Clinton last week that, under a final-status agreement, Israel
would be willing to recognize a Palestinian state on 70 to 80
percent of the West Bank land, a source in the Prime Minister's
Office confirmed Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that, although no exact details on the size of
the state were laid out by Barak, the leaders discussed various
informal proposals of the past.
</P>
<P>
These included a proposal by Regional Cooperation Minister
Shimon Peres, when he was prime minister, to give the Palestinians
80 percent of the West Bank and a suggestion of Minister in Prime
Minister's Office Haim Ramon, which is to annex 10 percent of the
West Bank, give the Palestinians 70 percent and leave 20 percent
under joint control for five to ten more years.
</P>
<P>
According to the source, Barak told Clinton that his position
was "closer to that of Peres," but that he did not envision giving
the Palestinians as much land as Peres had suggested.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Russia and Syria are expected to conclude a 500 million U.S.
dollars arms deal including advanced fighters and a sophisticated
air defense missile system, according to recent reports in the
Russian newspaper Vremya.
</P>
<P>
The deal is expected to take effect as early as this week and
includes 30 Sukhoi-27 air-superiority fighters and possibly the
very advanced long-range S-300 air defense missile system.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Syria is expected to receive another shipment of
Kornet and Metis advanced anti-tank guided missiles.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Justice Minister Yossi Beilin said Saturday that he sees no
reason why the last of the Lebanese hostages, Mustafa Dirani and
Sheikh Abdel Karim Obeid, need to be put on trial to keep them in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
"From my reading of the High Court decision, there is no reason
to believe that the Supreme Court will order them to be released if
there is a petition to that effect," said Beilin. "The court
stressed the importance of the security threat factor in
determining whether administrative detention was acceptable or not.
</P>
<P>
Security officials and Israel's Supreme Court Wednesday ordered
the release of 13 of the 15 Lebanese hostages being held in
administrative detention in Israel as bargaining chips for the
freedom of captive Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli stocks did not escape the chill that ran through Wall
Street last week and there is concern that the losses in share
prices on Nasdaq will be echoed in trading Sunday on the Tel Aviv
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the technology heave Nasdaq index fell by 10 percent,
bring its losses for the week to 25 percent. The Dow Jones index
also registered a significant decline, retreating 5.7 percent to a
level of 10,305.8 points. The Dow Jones lost a total of 7.3 percent
over the last week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli stocks continued on a downward trend
throughout the week, including Friday. This negative slide included
several large companies as well as smaller firms. 
