<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Truck Drivers' Strike Paralyzing Goods Transportation in Bangladesh By Pan Xiaozhu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The indefinite strike by truck
drivers and workers of Bangladesh entered its fourth consecutive
day on Sunday, paralyzing the transportation of goods across the
country.
</P>
<P>
The road communication across the country will be further
disrupted from Monday when workers of all modes of transports will
go on strike for an indefinite period in support of the truck
drivers and workers.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh Inter-District Truck Drivers Union enforced the
indefinite strike from Thursday across the country to press home
their three-point demand including release of its president and
other arrested leaders and workers.
</P>
<P>
Later, the Federation of Truck Workers also joined the strike
called by the Inter-District Truck Drivers Union.
</P>
<P>
The police recently arrested the President of the Union
Kafiluddin on charge of collecting tolls illegally from trucks and
other modes of transports.
</P>
<P>
The government had already launched a drive against illegal
toll takers. As part of the drive, the Ministry of Home Affairs
ordered demolition of illegal toll structures across the country.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladesh Road Transport Workers Federation will put their
vehicles off the roads all over the country from Monday for an
indefinite period of protest against the comment of a police chief.
</P>
<P>
Inspector General of Police (IGP) reportedly told local
newspaper on Wednesday that the government would no longer abide
by the compromise agreement that barred police from filing case
against any "killer" driver under Article 302 of the country's
Traffic Law.
</P>
<P>
The police used to file case against a "killer" driver under
Article 304 of the law that provides for a maximum punishment of
only three years in prison. Under the Article 302, the maximum
punishment is death sentence.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the Road Transport Workers Federation protested the
statement of the IGP, saying that no drivers would drive vehicles
with "hanging rope around their necks."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bangladesh Truck Drivers Union opposed the strike
for an indefinite period. Executive President Nur Mohammad of the
union in a statement to the press on Friday called upon the
transport workers to ignore the strike and put their vehicles on
the road.
</P>
<P>
He termed the strike as illogical because it would not
safeguard the interests of the drivers as a whole. He said that
the strike has been called "to protect the interests of vested
quarters." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000416.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Experts to Help Probe Kanungu Incident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Forensic experts and pathologists
from the British Metropolitan Police, the Scotland Yard, are
expected to arrive in Uganda soon to help probe the Kanungu
incident in which hundreds of people were killed.
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman Asuman Mugenyi told Xinhua in a telephone
interview on Sunday that Uganda needed help from foreign countries
especially in the field of forensic experts as far as the Kanungu
massacre is concerned.
</P>
<P>
He said the whole thing was beyond the capacity of Ugandan
police and experts from other foreign countries were also invited
to come in and take over the investigation work.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not reveal to which countries the Ugandan
police had sent invitation letters.
</P>
<P>
The foreign experts were also expected to study the mutilated
bodies exhumed from mass graves after the March 17 Kanungu
incident.
</P>
<P>
On March 17, over 530 people were burnt to death in a church
fire in Kanungu in southwestern Uganda by leaders of a cult
Movement for the Restoration of Ten Commandments of God. Hundreds
of bodies were later exhumed from at least five mass graves on
properties belonging to cult leaders.
</P>
<P>
Investigation and postmortem work was relatively slow due to
lack of advanced equipment and technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
