<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Going Back on Farms: Zimbabwean War Veterans' Head </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Chenjerai Hunzvi, leader of
Zimbabwean war veterans, Saturday made the vows that the
occupation of white-owned commercial farms will continue, The
Sunday Mail reported.
</P>
<P>
The veterans of the country's liberation struggle have invaded
more than 1,000 farms countrywide since February this year.
</P>
<P>
Addressing thousands of war veterans in Harare Saturday, Hunzvi
said, "I (have) no power to withdraw the war veterans from their
motherland. Even if I had power, it would be against my
conscience. I didn't send them there and I cannot and I will not
withdraw them."
</P>
<P>
Hunzvi accused the British government of interfering in
Zimbabwe's domestic affairs and urged war veterans to gather at
the Harare International Airport Sunday to welcome President
Robert Mugabe home from the Group of 77 economic summit in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
On April 7, Mugabe praised war veterans for invading
white-owned commercial farms, saying they were keeping the
liberation spirit alive.
</P>
<P>
Acting President Joseph Msika however ordered all the war
veterans and land hungry communal people to withdraw from the
farms to clear the way for an orderly resettlement on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said that it was no longer necessary for the former freedom
fighters to continue occupying the farms, because Parliament has
passed an Amendment Bill of the Constitution, which empowers the
government to acquire land from white farmers without
compensation.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the High Court ordered the state and the
police to move in and assist in the eviction of war veterans and
communal people on the occupied farms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
