<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian PM Outlines New Social Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Australian government would
spend 240 million Australian dollars (148.8 million U.S. dollars)
to improve access to child-care and to bolster family support
services as part of its new focus on social reform.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Howard Sunday announced the four-year
program in his keynote address to the ruling Liberal Party
national convention in Melbourne in southeast Australia.
</P>
<P>
Howard said while economic and taxation reform was crucial for
Australia, the changes must lead to a better social outcome for
Australians.
</P>
<P>
He said that under the Stronger Families Strategy, more money
would be spent to provide support for parents who needed help or
advice to raise children.
</P>
<P>
"Instead of isolating them, we should be reaching out to those
people who are crying out for help," Howard said.
</P>
<P>
He said that of the 240 million Australian dollars, 70 million
Australian dollars (43.4 million U.S. dollar) would be allocated
over four years to expand access to child-care services to people
who worked on shifts and in remote areas.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, child-care workers would come to the home and
possibly stay overnight, saving parents the need to disrupt a
child's routine by taking him or her to a child-care center.
</P>
<P>
"We should provide the option for the care to go to the home,
not the reverse," Howard said.
</P>
<P>
He said 4 million Australian dollars (2.48 million U.S. dollars)
would be spent on helping young people in isolated areas.
</P>
<P>
The money would fund 10,000 cadetships for young people in
isolated areas to help them take part in a wider range of
activities.
</P>
<P>
In his address, Howard also said the party faced significant
challenges and warned MPs and senators not to underestimate Labor'
s desire to win back power at the next election, due in late 2001.
</P>
<P>
"Never underestimate your political opponent," Howard said.
</P>
<P>
"I don't underestimate the challenge that lies ahead of the
coalition as it heads toward the next election," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
