<HEADLINE> Thai PM Rejects Proposal to Set Up Methamphetamine Factory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 16 (Xinhua) - Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
disagrees with the proposal of some academics for the state to set
up a factory to produce methamphetamine to fight traffickers of
this drug, the Thai News Agency (TNA) reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the Narcotic Control Board Sorasit Sangprasert quoted
the premier as expressing the disagreement to the proposal of some
academics that the state-run production would reduce the prices of
the illicit drug to the level that was unattractive to traffickers
and help rehabilitate methamphetamine addicts.
</P>
<P>
"Other countries would otherwise be confused with the
government's policy to fight the drug and methamphetamine would be
freely available in Thailand," Sorasit said.
</P>
<P>
The authorities were taking a right path in narcotic
suppression by arresting traffickers and rehabilitating addicts,
he said.
</P>
<P>
However, communities would have to throw more efforts to help
the state in the fight, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
