<DOCNO> XIE20000416.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Plans National Budget of 7,376 Million U.S. Dollars for Next Fiscal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The government of Bangladesh has
outlined the National Budget of 358.8 billion taka (7,376 million
U.S.dollars) for the 2000-2001 fiscal year with a target of
revenue earning of 248.8 billion taka (4,976 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The rest 110 billion taka (2,200 million dollars) is expected
to be
financed from foreign aid and other domestic sources, the
Bangladesh Observer reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The outline of the next budget is indicated in the country's
memorandum, presented at the Bangladesh Development Forum Meeting
held in Paris on April 13-14.
</P>
<P>
According to the memorandum, the size of the Annual Development
Program (ADP) for the coming fiscal is likely to be 165 billion
taka (3,300 million dollars) which is 10 billion taka (200 million
dollars) higher than the current ADP figure.
</P>
<P>
The revenue expenditure for the 2000-2001 fiscal is estimated
at 193 billion taka (3,860 million dollars) as against the
targeted revenue earning of 248.8 billion taka (4,976 million
dollars), thus leaving a surplus of 55.8 billion taka (1,116
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The National Budget for the current 1999-2000 fiscal targets
revenue earning of 241.51 billion taka (4,830 million dollars) as
against the revenue expenditure of 178 billion taka (3,560 million
dollars), leaving a surplus of 63.51 billion taka (1,270 million
dollars). But the government so far could not achieve the target
of revenue earning, resulting in huge shortfall in revenue budget.
</P>
<P>
At the annual meeting of the Bangladesh Development Forum in
Paris, donors agreed to give the country the 1.8-2.2 billion U.S.
dollars in aid for 2000-2001 fiscal. But the donors cautioned
Bangladesh that if the pace of reform was not accelerated and
rampant corruption not dealt with properly, the aid package might
be delayed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
