<HEADLINE> Indian President Leaves on State Visit to France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Indian President K.R. Narayanan
left here Sunday morning on a five-day state visit to France,
aiming at enhancing economic ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee, who saw the President off
at the airport, said that the visit, the first-ever by an Indian
head of state to France, will be a landmark in India's relations
with that country.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral ties between the two countries have been enhanced
after the strategic dialogue initiated between India and France
during Prime Minister Vajpayee's visit to France in September 1998.
</P>
<P>
An Investment Promotion Agreement is expected to be signed
during the visit in a bid to remove obstacles in trading between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral Trade in 1999 was in India's favor with exports
to France touching 900 million U.S. dollars and imports from
France at 680 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The French cumulative Foreign Direct Investment in India stood
at 1.4 billion dollars since 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
