<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Nepali Ambassador to China Urges Economic Cooperation By Zhuang Meijie, Song Dejun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Nepalese Ambassador to the
People's Republic of China stressed here on Saturday the need to
add economic dimensions to the long-standing friendship between
Nepal and China.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Rajeshwar Acharya said that the
good relations existing between Nepal and China in the political
sector should be expanded to the areas of economic cooperation for
the mutual benefits of the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
Recalling the long history of friendship between the two close
neighbors which share the Himalayan mountains, Acharya said Nepal
and China have excellent relationship both in the past and at
present.
</P>
<P>
"I believe this cordiality and good neighborliness will
continue in the future," he added.
</P>
<P>
"We do not have any disputes or outstanding issues, therefore,
Nepal has been providing support to China on national and
international issues," said the 53-year-old ambassador, who was
assigned to China one-and-half years ago and is now on a one-month
holiday here.
</P>
<P>
However, looking at the nature of our good relationship in
political sector, economic cooperation is far from enough, Acharya
regretted.
</P>
<P>
"Time has come for us to look into the economic dimension of
our partnership and make good use of our friendship for economic
development between our two countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics, the bilateral trade between Nepal
and China in 1999 stood at 215 million U.S. dollars, accounting
for less than three percent of Nepal's total foreign trade volume,
while Nepal-India trade occupies more than 60 percent in the same
year.
</P>
<P>
Acharya made a point of noting that to further develop economic
relations with China is the very policy of the Nepali new
government led by G.P. Koirala, who has put economic diplomacy at
the top of its foreign policy since he came into power last month.
</P>
<P>
"The new policy of the present Nepali government relating to
China is to let our good neighborliness and friendship be for the
mutual benefits of our two peoples and two countries," he
elaborated.
</P>
<P>
Talking on the prospect of economic cooperation between Nepal
and China, Acharya said "there are many areas where we can
cooperate," such as trade, investment, tourism, agriculture,
construction and transportation.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador drew a promising picture for Nepal-China joint
efforts in tapping the huge water resources in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
"We can achieve great benefits if we can work together for
harnessing the water resources, not only for generating
electricity, but also for multiple-use of water resources such as
irrigation, fishery, entertainment and so on," he said.
</P>
<P>
Acharya explained that the surplus power generated from water
can be exported to India, which is also in bad need of irrigation
water for its large areas of dry land.
</P>
<P>
As a mountainous country which has numerous rivers, Nepal
reserves a capacity of 83 million kilowatt hydro-power.
</P>
<P>
Claiming that Nepal can target the six South Asian neighbors as
a huge market for export, Acharya believed there were great
potentialities for Nepal-China joint ventures in manufacturing,
food-processing and even in agriculture production.
</P>
<P>
"Why not make good use of this advantage and set up joint
ventures," Acharya appealed to Chinese investors.
</P>
<P>
As to the query whether there are any barriers between Nepal
and China for trade and investment, Acharya said the only problem
is the lack of communications between the people of the two
countries which are not well-linked by roads.
</P>
<P>
"What I am doing now is to build up a bridge between Nepal and
China and to let people know more about each other," said the
ambassador, who has travelled to many cities in China, including
ancient cities of Xi'an, Luoyang and Kaifeng, as well as modern
cities such as Guangzhou, Shenzhen, Zhuhai and Shanghai, among
others.
</P>
<P>
During his visits to these cities, Acharya spared no pains to
pass the information about Nepal to Chinese officials and business
leaders in order to convince them of the great prospect of
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
As an economist who had studied the Nepalese economy for more
than 30 years, Acharya believes he is in a better position to
promote the economic relations between Nepal and China.
</P>
<P>
"To build the longest Nepal-China friendship for the future, I
am trying to advance the partnership in a larger scale in economic
areas," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
