<HEADLINE> Thailand to Recognize Use of Traditional Chinese Medicine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Public Health Ministry of
Thailand has approved a five-year plan to treat patients in
community hospitals with traditional Chinese medicine, the Bangkok
Post reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Khamron Na Lamphun, deputy health minister, was quoted as
saying that the use of Chinese medicine could be officially
adopted if found successful in the treatment of patients, even
though it was not officially recognized under current laws.
</P>
<P>
The Medical Registration Act allows the health minister to
approve the use of other methods of treatment which have not yet
been officially recognized.
</P>
<P>
Traditional Thai medicine is sometimes used to treat patients
even though Thailand only recognizes the use of modern medicine in
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
The medical registration division of the health ministry has
been asked to consider issuing temporary two-year licenses to
practitioners of traditional Chinese medicine.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal, only those trained in the art of Chinese
medicine and having more than five years' experience may apply for
the registration, Khamron said.
</P>
<P>
He said the applicants, who would be required to be Thai
citizens or spouses of Thai citizens, would be evaluated by a
committee under a cooperative program between the Thai and Chinese
governments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000416.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developing Countries Express Concern at Industrial Nations' Trade Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Excessive increases in short-term interest rates in major
industrial countries may negatively affect global growth prospects
and the cost of credit for the developing countries," said a
communique issued at the end of the 63rd meeting of the Ministers
of the Intergovernmental Group of Twenty-Four (G-24) on
International Monetary Affairs.
</P>
<P>
The communique said progress must be accelerated on lowering
barriers to developing country exports, especially granting full
access to all exports from the least developed countries in order
to help sustain global growth prospects and enhance poverty
reduction efforts.
</P>
<P>
The G-24 ministers emphasized in the communique the need for a
well-sequenced and balanced approach toward the further
integration of developing countries, particularly the poorest,
into the global trading system.
</P>
<P>
They were of the view that the World Bank and the regional
development banks have an important role to play in capacity
building and infrastructure development to further and accelerate
that integration.
</P>
<P>
The preparation of Poverty Reduction Strategy Papers (PRSPs) in
a participatory process is a demanding and time-consuming
undertaking for the Highly Indebted Poor Countries (HIPCs), which
should not delay the provision of debt relief, the communique said.
</P>
<P>
The ministers expressed deep concern regarding the
insufficiency of contributions from donor countries for the HIPC
Trust Fund to finance the share of debt relief from the World Bank
and other multilaterals.
</P>
<P>
They have strong reservations regarding any significant
shortening of maturity for International Monetary Fund (IMF)
facilities that are provided in support of members experiencing
balance of payments disequilibrium of a structural character and
that could not be corrected in short order.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the G-24 member countries also expressed their
concern at proposals to reform the IMF and the World Bank,
particularly any changes that could make it more difficult for
them to obtain loans or have to pay them back faster.
</P>
<P>
"We find some of these proposals unacceptable and have serious
concerns about them," said German Suarez, chairman of the G-24, at
a press conference after the group's meeting. "But we support
efforts to reform" the IMF and the World Bank and "strengthen
cooperation between them."
</P>
<P>
Suarez referred to the so-called Meltzer Report, written by a
commission led by Carnegie Mellon University Professor Alan
Meltzer. The report recommended that the IMF should stop lending
to the world's poorest nations, many of which are African, and
leave development financing to the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also rejected conclusions of a U.S. congressional
committee that the IMF should limit itself to short term lending
and the World Bank should halt loans to middle income countries.
</P>
<P>
The G-24 meets twice a year at the deputies and the ministerial
level and makes proposals to the Interim Committee of the Board of
Governors of the IMF and the Development Committee of the Board of
Governors of the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
It consists of an important cross section of countries across
Africa, Asia and Latin America. Since its establishment in 1972,
the G-24 has become the primary institutional mechanism for the
coordination of developing country positions on monetary affairs.
</P>
<P>
The group comprises Algeria, Argentina, Brazil, Colombia, Cote
d'Ivoire, Egypt, Ethiopia, Gabon, Ghana, Guatemala, India, Iran,
Lebanon, Mexico, Nigeria, Pakistan, Peru, the Philippines, the
Republic of Congo, Sri Lanka, Syria, Trinidad-Tobago, Venezuela
and Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000416.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Industrial Nations Promise to Support Global Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Group of Seven (G-7)
leading industrial nations Saturday promised to cooperate with
other countries to promote global prosperity.
</P>
<P>
In a communique released after a meeting of G-7 finance
ministers and central bank governors, the world's seven wealthiest
countries said they agreed on the continued importance of
directing both macroeconomic and structural policies "in all our
countries at this objective, with emphasis on taking full
advantage of the investment opportunities created by new
technologies to raise potential growth rates."
</P>
<P>
"We re-emphasized our commitment to maintain or create
conditions for strong, sustainable growth in each of our countries,
" the communique said.
</P>
<P>
The finance ministers also pledged to keep pushing ahead with
reforms of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The communique said in the context of the changing global
financial landscape, in particular the increasing importance of
private global capital markets, it is appropriate for the
international community to continue to examine the role and
functioning of the international financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
"We also agreed to continue our work to implement fully the
wide range of measures to strengthen the international financial
architecture endorsed at the Cologne summit last June, including
promoting appropriate private sector involvement," it noted.
</P>
<P>
However, the ministers tacitly acknowledged that the Highly
Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) initiative was not running well.
</P>
<P>
"We reaffirm the importance we attach to bringing countries
quickly to the point where they can benefit from debt relief," the
communique said.
</P>
<P>
The G-7 agreed in Cologne to radically overhaul the existing
HIPC scheme which had failed to deliver any meaningful debt relief
to the world's 40-odd poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
The ministers welcomed the initiation of World Trade
Organization (WTO) negotiations in agriculture and services and
supported efforts to build a consensus for the early launch of a
new round of multilateral trade negotiations designed to bring
benefit to all countries, including the poorest.
</P>
<P>
They called on the IMF and the World Bank to work with the WTO
and other relevant institutions to improve the effectiveness of
trade-related technical assistance, and to more fully incorporate
policies promoting international trade and capacity building into
IMF programs and World Bank operations.
</P>
<P>
The group's communique did not specifically mention the huge
plunge in U.S. stock prices last week, but the officials stressed
an upbeat view of growth prospects for the global economy which
they said "continue to brighten."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference after the G-7 meeting, U.S.
Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said despite the huge U.S.
stock sell-off, in which nearly 2 trillion U.S. dollars of wealth
was lost in a single week, "the momentum of the expansion is very
much in place. ... There will be fluctuations from quarter to
quarter, but our economy is strong." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
