<HEADLINE> S. Lankan Govt Rejects Rebel Demand On Troops Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
rejected a "demand" by Tamil rebels for troops withdrawals in
northern Jaffna Peninsula for peace talks, according to a
statement from the Foreign Ministry here.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry, in a statement issued Saturday evening, said top
rebel official Anton Balasingham in a media interview in London,
said government troops withdrawal could take place only if a
permanent political solution is reached.
</P>
<P>
Balasingham, the Tamil rebel theoretician, told the Tamil "
Guardian" magazine in London last month that the troops should
remove "a complex set of repressive conditions....on the Tamil
people."
</P>
<P>
Balasingham, who is now reportedly based in the United Kingdom
and travels the continent on rebel propaganda work, also wanted a
program of disengagement, a cease-fire and reallocation of
government troops back to their barracks.
</P>
<P>
The statement said "the government rejected Balasingham's
suggestion that repressive conditions are being imposed on the
Tamil people."
</P>
<P>
The government wishes to reiterate that the prevailing security
measures could not be dismantled, as long as the Tamil rebels
continue on its path of violence and destruction, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the government troops operating in predominantly
Tamil areas, particularly Jaffna peninsula, have shown a high
degree of professionalism in protecting the Tamil people despite
grave provocation by the rebels, while at the same time
safeguarding the territorial integrity of Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The Jaffna peninsula was once the stronghold of the Tamil
rebels who have been fighting a war for a separate Tamil state in
the north and east of the country since 1983. The peninsula was
recaptured by the government troops in may 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
