<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Imports Large Bulk of Machinery in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar imported machinery
equipment valued at 701 million U.S. dollars in 1999, a drop of 32.
98 percent from 1998 when it was recorded at 1.046 billion dollars,
according to the latest figures released by the country's Central
Statistical Organization.
</P>
<P>
During the year, the import volume of such machinery equipment
accounted for 29 percent of the total import volume which was 2.41
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Of them, the import volume of non-electric machinery and
transport equipment reached 456 million dollars, falling by 42.64
percent as compared with 1998 when it registered 795 million
dollars, while that of electrical machinery and apparatus amounted
to 245 million dollars, a drop of 2.4 percent from 1998 when it
showed 251 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is an agricultural country lacking development in
industry. The majority of its required different machinery
equipment has to depend on import. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000416.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaragua on Alert Against Cholera in Border Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Nicaraguan authorities are
tightening control on cholera, especially in the border areas
with Honduras and El Salvador where outbreaks of the epidemic have
been reported.
</P>
<P>
El Salvador has reported three deaths and 200 cases of cholera,
while Honduras has decreed an epidemiological quarantine in the
border area with Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry said Saturday it will reinforce its health
brigades, medicine inventories and sanitary personnel in the zone
of Rio Coco, bordering with Honduras. It also called on the
population to boil drinking water.
</P>
<P>
These measures aim to prevent reinfection of the lethal disease
which has been under control in the country, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
In Nicaragua, 291 cases of cholera infection and five deaths
were reported last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
