<HEADLINE> Brazil, Mexico to Discuss Agreement on Customs Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Brazil and Mexico are to discuss
a bilateral customs tariffs agreement for agricultural and
industrial products Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is expected to propose that the tariffs on soybean cake
and oil, now at 18 percent and 10 percent respectively between the
two countries, be reduced to zero.
</P>
<P>
Experts at the Brazilian Agriculture Ministry expected to
double the soybean cake export and increase the sales of soybean
oil if an agreement is struck with Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Brazil exported 100,000 tons of soybean cake, while
the sales of soybean oil were practically zero, according to the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's another major export is orange juice, for which the
tariff imposed by Mexico is 23 percent, the ministry's agriculture
policy secretary Benedito Rosa de Espiritu Santo said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The most sensitive products for the negotiation are raw hides,
footwear, lumber, paper and cellulose, he said.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is reluctant to import electronics, chemicals and
petrochemicals from Mexico for fear that U.S. industries in Mexico
might inundate the Brazilian market with their products, according
to the secretary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
