<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Education News in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The following is a review of
major education stories Xinhua released from April 10 to April 15:
</P>
<P>
Aid For Education In China's Western Regions
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Communist Party Central Committee and the State
Council issued a circular recently calling for further support and
aid to schools in China's western regions.
</P>
<P>
It called on schools in relatively well-off regions in eastern
China to provide support and aid to their counterparts in the west.
</P>
<P>
MOE Trains Over 3,000 High School Headmasters
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Education (MOE) has trained over 3,000 high
school headmasters in the past decade since it established a
training center for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
The training center, located at East China Teachers' University,
has held 19 terms of research classes for provincial-level key
high school headmasters, two terms for national key high school
headmasters, and three rounds for Hong Kong high school
headmasters.
</P>
<P>
BU Establishes High-Tech Park in Xinjiang
</P>
<P>
China's prestigious Beijing University (BU) will establish a
high-tech park in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region in the
northwest this May, in a bid to promote the local economy of the
area.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Urumqi Economic Development Zone in this
capital of Xinjiang said that the 33.3-hectare park will include
research facilities for projects involving microbe fertilizer,
wind power usage, and bio-plastic sheeting.
</P>
<P>
Education Website Opened in Beijing
</P>
<P>
A website devoted to the continuous education of the Chinese
people officially opened in Beijing on April 11.
</P>
<P>
The website: www.eol.com.cn, created by the Enterprises Group
of prestigious Qinghua University, is targeting visitors between
the ages of 16 and 35 who are open-minded and keen on learning. (
more)
</P>
