<DOCNO> XIE20000416.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are highlights of
major environment stories Xinhua released during the past week:
</P>
<P>
China to Better Protect Black Finless Dolphins
</P>
<P>
-- Experts from the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) said that
the black finless dolphin is becoming an endangered species in the
Yangtze River and it should be better protected, along with the
white-finned dolphin.
</P>
<P>
The number of black finless dolphins, which have a habitat
similar to that of the white-finned dolphin, one of the world's
most endangered species, is less than 2,000, and compared with 2,
700 in 1993, their number is shrinking by more than 100 a year.
</P>
<P>
Scientist Calls for Nature Reserve for Rare Yangtze River Fish
</P>
<P>
-- A Chinese scientist recently called for the creation of a
nature reserve along the Chishui River, a tributary on the upper
reaches of the Yangtze River, for rare and endangered fish.
</P>
<P>
During an academic meeting on sustainable development in
western China, Cao Wenxuan, an academician of the Chinese Academy
of Sciences (CAS), said the Chishui is a perfect habitat for the
rare fish of the Yangtze, and it is not suitable to build a
hydraulic power plant on the river.
</P>
<P>
Scientists Study Effect of Environmental Changes On People's
Health
</P>
<P>
-- A group of scientists with the Chinese Academy of Geology
studied the effect of environmental changes over the past 100
years on people's health in large industrial cities.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that about a quarter of human diseases are
connected with the environment. Acute respiratory diseases caused
by air pollution kill over four million children worldwide every
year.
</P>
<P>
China Names 33 Ecological Demonstration Counties, Prefectures
</P>
<P>
-- Thirty-three counties and prefectures across China were
named as ecological demonstration areas by the State Environmental
Protection Administration of China (SEPA).
</P>
<P>
The areas, including Yanqing County in northern Beijing, are
the first in China to have met the economic, social, and
environmental requirements of China's sustainable development
strategy.
</P>
<P>
China's Island Province to Ban "White Pollution"
</P>
<P>
-- China's island province of Hainan has formally stopped
approving new production line of foam plastic dishware and urged
producers to build recycle system to reduce "white pollution".
</P>
<P>
All dishware producers are required to build proper recycle
system within one year and have been requested to increase the
production of degradable plastics.
</P>
<P>
The government hopes the efforts will help increase the
recycling of plastics to 95 percent.
</P>
<P>
Shandong to Enlarge Swan Lake
</P>
<P>
-- The Swan Lake in Rongcheng City, the world's largest habitat
for swans in east China's Shandong Province, is to be enlarged
from 6,600 to more than 10,000 hectares with a total investment of
25 million yuan (3.01 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The lake, which is an ideal habitat for swans in winter,
attracts thousands of swans from Siberia every year to spend
winter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000416.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- A leading Chinese scholar has urged greater attention to
ecological protection while developing the vast western region,
which is suffering from a deteriorating environment.
</P>
<P>
The forest area of most of western China is sparse, with the
coverage rate for the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region only 0.79
percent, and 0.35 percent for Qinghai Province, 1.54 percent for
Ningxia, 4.33 percent for Gansu and 5.84 percent for the Tibet
Autonomous Region, said Jiang Zehui, president of the Chinese
Academy of Forestry.
</P>
<P>
Scientists Suggest Applying High-tech to Control Desert
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese scientists have suggested introducing high-tech
methods to control the deteriorating desertification of northwest
China, which has caused several severe dust storms this spring.
</P>
<P>
The high-tech should include biotechnology, chemistry and water-
saving technologies, said Shan Lun, an academician with the Soil
and Water Conservation Institute under the Chinese Academy of
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Rare Grouse Confirmed Extinct in Northeast China
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese experts have confirmed that a rare kind of grouse
living in frigid zones is extinct in China.
</P>
<P>
The extinct spruce grouse, belonging to the species of
ptarmigan, only inhabits coniferous forests in frigid zones.
</P>
<P>
During a five-year investigation, researchers searched all the
possible habitats in China of spruce grouse but found none, said
Yu Xiaolian, an expert with the Heilongjiang Research Institute of
Wild Life.
</P>
<P>
Foreign loans to Aid Eco-Protection in Inner Mongolia
</P>
<P>
-- Foreign loans are expected to play an important role in
ecological protection endeavors in north China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The region has up to now received interest-free loans of some
360 million yuan (about 43.2 million US dollars) from Germany and
Japan for improving the environment, said Zhou Luming, an official
with the regional Bureau of Forestry.
</P>
<P>
Gansu Begins Massive Afforestation Campaign
</P>
<P>
-- For several days, thousands of people from all walks of life
have participated a tree-planting campaign in Lanzhou, capital of
northwest China's Gansu province.
</P>
<P>
Lanzhou municipal Party and government officials and soldiers
also planted trees on two major mountains, Northern Mountain and
Southern Mountain, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
Shelterbelt in N.E. China Helps Fight Desertification
</P>
<P>
-- A forest shelterbelt network which has been established in
northeast China's Jilin province has helped decrease land
threatened by desertification from 7.3 million hectares in the
1970s to 2.53 million hectares.
</P>
<P>
The province launched four major shelterbelts projects at the
beginning of the 1990s. In the past eight years, the province
planted 120,000 hectare of trees, increasing the province's forest
coverage from 10.3 percent to 12.4 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000416.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
1st Temporary Storage for Nuclear Waste Set up in Southwest
China
</P>
<P>
-- China has recently set up its first advanced temporary
storage for nuclear wastes discharged from civilian-use reactors
in southwest China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
The storage is built by the Nuclear Power Research and Design
Institute of China to hold solid nuclear waste and other
radioactive waste materials. Some of the waste will be disposed of
permanently by burying it deep underground, an official with the
State Environmental Protection Administration of China (SEPA) said.
</P>
<P>
China Sets Up Radiation Monitoring Center
</P>
<P>
-- A state radiation monitoring technical center was set up in
this capital city of east China's Zhejiang Province on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Affiliated with the State Environmental Protection
Administration, the center will enhance China's nuclear safety and
radiation management, improve technical management levels, collect
and analyze statistical data, and training technical personnel.
</P>
<P>
World Scientists Discuss Environmental Issues in Beijing
</P>
<P>
-- More than 100 Chinese and foreign scientists attended a
symposium of the Scientific Committee on Problem of Environment (
SCOPE) under the International Council of Scientific Unions (ICSU),
from April 14 to 18 in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that SCOPE have ever held a seminar in
China. The theme of the symposium is promoting eco-development in
developing regions.
</P>
<P>
First Zoo for Wild Animals in Northwest China
</P>
<P>
-- Construction of northwest China's first zoo for wild animals
has begun in the city of Wuzhong in the Ningxia Hui Autonomous
Region with the approval of the State Forestry Administration.
</P>
<P>
The zoo, to be built at a cost of 230 million yuan (about 28
million U.S. dollars), will cover an area of 667 hectares.
Construction will be carried out in three stages and the first
stage will be completed in three years. By then the zoo will have
more than 100 species of wild animals and plants.
</P>
<P>
North China Suffers Severe Drought
</P>
<P>
-- Four consecutive years of severe drought have evaporated the
drinking water of nearly 1.5 million people in north China's Hebei
Province which surrounds Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Hebei is facing a shortage of 800 million cubic meters of water,
said Wang Jun, deputy director of the provincial flood control and
drought relief office.
</P>
<P>
Greater Effort Urged to Improve Environment Around Beijing
</P>
<P>
-- Greater effort must be made to improve the environment in
areas around the Chinese capital of Beijing, a senior Beijing
official said in a recent interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"This brooks no delay," said Song Xiyou, director of the
Beijing Municipal Afforestation Bureau.  
</P>
