<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Education News in China (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Ministry of Education said on April 13 it was pleased with
the report of high employment rates for this year's 1.07 million
college graduates.
</P>
<P>
Postgraduates and students from well-known universities are
being actively pursued by employers, Qu Zhenyuan, an official with
the ministry, said at a briefing in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
University graduates are in great demand in developed provinces
and cities in eastern and coastal areas, but the need is far less
in the underdeveloped western region, Qu said.
</P>
<P>
China Raises College Enrollment Quota
</P>
<P>
China's colleges and universities will enroll 1.8 million
freshmen this autumn term, an increase of 200,000 over last year's
total, an official with the Ministry of Education said on April 13.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will also enroll 120,000 graduate students this
year, 95,000 of whom will pursue master's degrees.
</P>
<P>
Over half of China's universities will use on-line enrollment
this year.
</P>
<P>
Southeast China University Merges Three Colleges in Nanjing
</P>
<P>
In the current national drive to merge colleges and
universities, prestigious Southeast China University in Nanjing,
capital of East China's Jiangsu Province, annexed three local
colleges on April 14.
</P>
<P>
Southeast China University, founded in 1902, is one of the
first institutions of higher learning in China. It was known as
National Central University in the first half of this century.
</P>
<P>
The university, famous for its engineering program, has merged
the Nanjing Railway Medical College, Nanjing Transportation
College and Nanjing Geological School to further strengthen its
advantage in engineering and science studies.
</P>
<P>
New Network Solution Debuts on Chinese Campuses
</P>
<P>
A new network solution that is expected to improve information
exchange on campuses made its trial run in three Chinese
universities on April 14.
</P>
<P>
CampusAge, created by a group of Qinghua University students,
was designed to remedy the inconvenience and limited flow of
information on campuses by providing students with on-line
services and news releases about their schools.
</P>
<P>
Using 6.6 million yuan in funding, the Qinghua students put
their studies on hold in January to start a new Internet website,
FanSo.com. 
</P>
</TEXT>
