<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2110 GMT, Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel will invited an expert team of the United
States Defense Department to help it map out the exact borderline
with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The team is due to arrive in the region at the invitation of
Israeli government in the coming days to begin work immediately,
the Jerusalem Post daily quoted Israeli Defense Ministry sources as
saying on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The idea was reportedly the result of consultations in
Washington last week between U.S. defense officials and an Israeli
delegation, headed by Defense Ministry Deputy Director-General
Moshe Kochanovsky and officials from the Israel Defense Forces
(IDF) cartography department. (Israel-US-Border)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- One person was confirmed dead, one injured very
seriously and eight other slightly or moderately in a roof collapse
accident in Israel on Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
The tragedy took place on a construction site of a shopping
center at the eastern entrance of Tira, a small town north of Tel
Aviv, according to Israel Radio reports.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary reports from police showed the major cause of the
accident might be negligence of the project engineer, architect and
contractor, whom a police investigation team is trying to locate.
</P>
<P>
The injured had been transferred to nearby hospitals. (Israel-
Collapse-Casualties)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Foreign Ministry on Sunday rejected foreign
interference in the trial on 13 Iranian Jews accused of espionage
for Tehran's arch foes -- the United States and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has warned that the conduct and outcome of the trial
could affect the thaw in relations that began only after the
election of the moderate President Mohammad Khatami in 1997, while
France and Germany have called for a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
The 13 Iranian Jews along with eight Muslims were arrested in
March and April last year on charges of spying for the U.S. and
Israel, who have denied any connection with them. (Iran-Jews)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Transportation Minister Yitzhak Mordechai
is facing indictment on three counts of sexual assault and sexual
harassment based on complaints filed by three women, police
spokeswoman said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The police investigation team for the case ended their probe
Sunday afternoon and turned the findings to the State Attorney's
Office, saying that they collected enough evidence to support their
recommendations to charge Mordechai with indecent sexual acts with
force. (Israel-Minister-Harassment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
