<HEADLINE> Jordanian King, Canadian PM Meet on Ties, Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
met with visiting Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien here on
Sunday to discuss ways of cementing bilateral ties and the latest
developments in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
On economic cooperation, Abdullah and Chretien reviewed Jordan's
investment opportunities for Canadian private businessmen in such
sectors as tourism, fertilizers, software industry and information
technology.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah also expressed his appreciation for Canada's
contribution to the Jordanian economy by providing support to a
series of development projects in the kingdom, Jordan's official
news agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
On the peace process in the region, both Abdullah and Chretien
expressed support for all efforts aimed at achieving progress on
all tracks in line with relevant United Nations resolutions to
achieve a just, comprehensive and durable peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
The king stressed that Canada can play an important role on
multilateral negotiations, particularly on the thorny refugee
issues in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that peace in the region should be based on
justice and equality with opportunities given to all the countries
in the region to concentrate on economic and social developments to
pave the way for prosperity of the people.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Chretien said his country is ready to support the
Jordanian economy as the kingdom has made efforts to integrate its
economy with the world economy and has embarked on various economic
reform programs.
</P>
<P>
He also commended Jordan upon its efforts to help parties
concerned to overcome obstacles in the peace process after the
kingdom signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994, the second Arab
country after Egypt to strike a peace deal with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian leader arrived in Amman on Friday on the fifth leg
of his regional tour, which has taken him to Israel, Palestinian
territories, Egypt and Lebanon and will also take him to Syria and
Saudi Arabia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
