<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Company Developing Gene-altered Salmon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Massachusetts-based AF Protein, which is carrying out its
research on Prince Edward Island, expects these new super-fish to
be cleared for consumer consumption within a year.
</P>
<P>
If given the green light, these fish would be the first
genetically modified (GM) animal to hit the market. The technology
could drastically change the way fish are farmed since the
technique cuts the cost of raising certain species such as salmon
and trout in half.
</P>
<P>
To get the Atlantic salmon to grow at such great speed, the
company inserted into the fish a gene sequence for growth hormones
from the Chinook salmon and genes that activate those hormones.
</P>
<P>
As a result, instead of producing growth hormone mostly in the
summer months, the genetically modified Atlantic salmon will
produce it year round.
</P>
<P>
But GM opponents are worried that some of the salmon could get
out, mix with non-GM fish and consequently taint the gene pool.
</P>
<P>
For its part, AF Protein maintains that its genetically
modified salmon are all tested to be sterile and pose no threat of
contamination to the wider salmon population.
</P>
<P>
Genetically modified food remains a hotly debated issue among
consumers, activists and environmentalists. Once the new Atlantic
salmon gets ready to hit supermarket shelves, the debate will only
heat up more. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000416.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Demands Zimbabwe to Prevent Killings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Britain on Sunday summoned
Zimbabwe's High Commissioner in London, demanding that Zimbabwe
President Robert Mugabe prevent further killings and violence in
the southern African state.
</P>
<P>
"It is essential that peace and stability are achieved quickly
and the rule of law upheld," Foreign Office Minister Peter Hain
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Hain said he also told Zimbabwe's High Commissioner in London,
Simbarashe Mumbengegwi, that Britain was "gravely concerned" by
recent events in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"It is also important for leadership to be given from the very
top of government to prevent further lawlessness and violence,"
Hain said, signalling that Britain held Mugabe responsible for the
situation.
</P>
<P>
Following the summons, Mumbengegwi said he regretted the farmer
's murder.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook urged African
nations to pressure President Mugabe to end a black invasion of
white farmlands and prevent further bloodshed in the former
British colony.
</P>
<P>
Cook told reporters during a visit to India that Mugabe was
overseeing "the destruction of his own country".
</P>
<P>
"The situation is very grave. I'm worried it will get worse
unless there is a return to respect for the rule of law in
Zimbabwe," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, who has been in power for 20 years since Britain's
last African colony won independence, has said the occupations are
a response to a historic injustice which left a few thousand white
farmers in control of the country's best land.  
</P>
</TEXT>
